@NODE "Mail_0" ".res files and "|""
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Tue, 24 Nov 1998 06:31:31 -0500
Subject: .res files and "|"

Hi Everyone,

A couple of questions:

First, I often see examples here that use structures and constants from one
or more .res files.  The constants I find in the AutoDocs.  But where do I
find descriptions of the Blitz NewType structures that are used?  Is there
some way to look into the .res files to see what's in them? 


Second, I often see people combining several flag values into one hex number
in their code.  I prefer to use the flags individually, separated by the
"|", as it makes it easier for me later to see and change the flags I have
used, rather than "reverse-engineering" the hex number.  So, my question
is, is there any advantage to combining the flags into one number?  Does it
make the code faster or smaller, or is this just a matter of style?

Thanks...
-- 
The man who can smile when things go
wrong has thought of someone to blame it on.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_1" "Re: .res files and "|""
 (envelope-from D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    24 Nov 98 12:46:41 0
From: "David Mcminn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Tue, 24 Nov 1998 12:46:35 -0000
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: .res files and "|"

On 24 Nov 98, at 6:31, Curt Esser wrote:

> First, I often see examples here that use structures and constants from
> one or more .res files.  The constants I find in the AutoDocs.  But wher=
e
> do I find descriptions of the Blitz NewType structures that are used?  I=
s
> there some way to look into the .res files to see what's in them? 

 The OS3.1 C includes is where to find them (available on Devs CD). 
There was also a Blitz version of these (possibly and earlier version 
of the OS) but I think it was only available when you purchased the 
Library Developper pack from Acid. Unless its on Ultimate Blitz CD, 
along with other stuff that shouldn't be there ;) Some structures are 
also described in the RKRMs and probably in "Amiga Guru Book", but I 
wouldn't know as I don't have it.

> Second, I often see people combining several flag values into one hex
> number in their code.  I prefer to use the flags individually, separated
> by the "|", as it makes it easier for me later to see and change the fla=
gs
> I have used, rather than "reverse-engineering" the hex number.  So, my
> question is, is there any advantage to combining the flags into one
> number?  Does it make the code faster or smaller, or is this just a matt=
er
> of style?

 Its better to use | I think, as this seems to be a standard way of 
combining flags (in C anyway). The executable should be exactly the 
same size and speed either way. Constants combined with | will get 
combined at compile time to produce one number, which is the same as 
assigning anew constant.


|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
  d.mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk ICQ=3D16827694


