@NODE "Mail_46" "Re: AGA or CyberGFX/P96 Screen"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Sat, 21 Nov 1998 01:37:49 +0000
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: AGA or CyberGFX/P96 Screen
Date: Sat, 21 Nov 1998 01:37:56 -0000
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit


-----Original Message-----
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: 20 November 1998 20:15
Subject: AGA or CyberGFX/P96 Screen


Hi Paul,


>Does anyone know how to test if a given DisplayID is for an
>AGA (Native Amiga) screen or an RTG (CGFX/P96) screen?

There should be a way of checking, as I have some screen grabber software
that *claims* to grab chunky bitmaps correctly, but I`ve never gotten around
to debuging it to see how it does it...if I do get some *spare* time..I`ll
report my findings on the list :).


>
>Ohh, and the type of mode should be detected *before* the
>screen is opened although I would consider 'after open'
>checks if there was no other way.
>

Well, I simply check the amount of chip mem free, before and after opening a
screen. This then told me if it was using chipmem for the bitmap (I used a
forbid/permit around the routine to stop other programs eating chip).

>BTW, I have tried some methods myself but with no success
>so please don't suggest anything unless you're confident it
>actually works...
>


I haven`t found any problem with that way of checking (ie, all aga screens
must use chipmem and all gfx cards have their own memory...unless you know
different!).

Dave



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_47" "Re: AGA or CyberGFX/P96 Screen"
 (envelope-from FlameDuck@usa.net)
 (envelope-from FlameDuck@usa.net)
From: Mikkel =?iso-8859-1?Q?L=F8kke?= <FlameDuck@usa.net>
Date: Sat, 21 Nov 1998 20:08:36 +0200
Organization: A97
Subject: Re: AGA or CyberGFX/P96 Screen
Encoding: quoted-printable

Hello Paul.

On 20-Nov-98, Paul Burkey wrote:

> Does anyone know how to test if a given DisplayID is for an
> AGA (Native Amiga) screen or an RTG (CGFX/P96) screen?
> The DisplayID is of the kind returned by ASL requester and used
> in the ScreenTag #SA_DisplayID =


Yes, and no. As I have no graphics board I'm not quite sure this works.

> I've now merged the AGA and RTG version of Foundation into
> one single exe file that *should* be able to know which type
> of graphics rendering to use. The AGA mode will use c2p code
> an the RTG mode will use WritePixelArray8() I could of course
> provide an AGA/RTG gadget so the user can tell me which
> mode they selected but that doesn't look very clever :)

Their are basically two ways to solve this problem.

1. I am told that once you know the displayID of a screen you can get all=

sorts of info in C style struct, structures. However, since I have only
recently begun system programming, I do not know how. I know that DpaintV=

does it. Another problem is that P96 allows you to define your own
DisplayID's, so as not to clash with other software.

2. RTGMaster.library ? A very cool "program", has it's own screenmode
requester, which does return chunky/planar information. Even if you where=

not interested in using these optimised routines for chunky graphics, it
seems you could still use the requestor....

I personally prefer the RTGMaster way.


Regards
