Subject: Re: Straight lines

Hi,

>> (Given A(x1,y1) and B(x2,y2) and that the line is from A to B)
>> 
>> X <-- x1
>> Y <-- y1

> Sorry if this is a dumb question, but could you please explain what the
> "<--" operator means?  I've never seen this one before.  I was guessing i=
t
> was the same as "=", but then "=" appears in other places.  Thanks.

sorry, it's just pseudo-code which is simple to port to any language. You'l=
l
find many types of pseudo-code, some standard and some 'made up on
the spot' and they all use their own rules. I don't know if this flavour of
pseudo-code is a standard one, i din't actually construct it myself.

>> X <-- x1

It does indeed mean '='... I'm not sure why <-- was used.
 
>>    DeltaX = -DeltaX

I suppose the '=' is used in a slightly different context here but you're
right to say that '=' would have been enough.

Cheers,

