@NODE "Mail_118" "Re: Correct use of CludgeBitmap + Free Bitmap"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Sun, 22 Nov 1998 04:04:59 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 22 Nov 98 04:01:24 +0000
Subject: Re: Correct use of CludgeBitmap + Free Bitmap
Encoding: 7bit

Burkey,

> 
> I reserve some memory then use CludgeBitmap to force the new
> bitmap to use my reserved memory. Then later in the code I
> need to free both the bitmap and the memory. What order should
> this be done in? I guess, 'free bitmap' then 'freemem'.. 
> 
> Does this explain the point behind the bitmaps _isreal element?

The isreal element is used to say wether or not the bitmap object has
allocated some memory or wether it has cludged it from some that
existed. If you free the bitmap before freeing the cludged memory it
should just kill the bitmap object and leave the memory alone. You can
then free the cludged memory. I think that if you free the cludged
memory first and then free the bitmap object without having done any
output to the bitmap inbetween, things should still be safe. You only
need worry if you kill the cludged memory, draw something to the
bitmap and then free the bitmap.

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk



