@NODE "Mail_131" "DefLibs"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Tue, 17 Nov 1998 05:41:02 -0500
Subject: DefLibs

Hi,

On 15-Nov-98, James L Boyd wrote:

> Yeah, but whatever we use, it'll clash with somebody else's setup.
> I suppose we just have to sort it out ourselves for our particular
> system...pity there's no official setup (and more library spaces)...

Well, it really doesn't matter what numbers you use with FDconverted
librarys when distributing them - the DefLibMan program also allows you to
change the library numbers.

But does anybody know if it really makes any difference if AmigaLibs have
numbers >200 or not?  I have some with lower numbers, and everything still
seems to work OK.

Is this really just a "style" thing, or will lower numbers for AmigaLibs
cause problems that I am not aware of?

And nice work on the Fdconvert utility, James.  Much handier to use (for me
anyway)


                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_132" "Re: DefLibs"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Tue, 17 Nov 1998 07:08:45 -0500
Subject: Re: DefLibs

Hi Toby,

On 17-Nov-98, Toby Zuijdveld wrote:
> On 17-Nov-98, Curt Esser set out across the seas with this message:

> ->Well, it really doesn't matter what numbers you use with FDconverted
> ->librarys when distributing them - the DefLibMan program also allows
> ->change the library numbers.
> 
> It does?  How?  =]

Sorry, I should have said the BlitzLibMan program that James had
recommended.
The only problem I had with it is that it won't recognize the
"Blitzlibs:otherlibs/"
directory that is used with newer versions of Blitz.  But if you rename this
directory to "userlibs" it will work fine, and has a button that lets you
change the number of any selected library.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
