@NODE "Mail_141" "Re: DefLibs... arrrgh!"
          (Post.Office MTA Undefined release Undefined
          ID# 0-52107U250000L250000S0V35) with SMTP id net
          for <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>; Wed, 18 Nov 1998 21:06:34 +0000
From: "Xyz Scott" <xyz.scott@virgin.net>
Subject: Re: DefLibs... arrrgh!
Date: Wed, 18 Nov 1998 21:00:52 -0000
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

On the 18-Nov-1998 Curt Esser said:

>> I usually have to change any new lib number so it doesn't clash with
>> existing libs. This is easily done by using a hex editor and editing
>> the 38th byte of the .obj file to whatever number, and then recompiling
>> DefLibs (or not Mikkel (; )  although I'm sure you all knew that.

>I didn't - good to know.  But if the lib number is in the 38th byte, does
>this mean that library numbers are really limited to 0-255?  Or is it safe
>to alter both the 38th and 39th bytes?


Unfortunately we are limited to library numbers 0-255.  For the library
number
to be a 16 bit number, it would be the 37th and 38th bytes, and if you alter
both of these, the LibMan deflibs compiler recognizes the 16 bit number and
will compile your deflibs, but the Blitz editor won't tokenize it (you just
get
the familiar ?????).  If there is a way around this though, could someone
let
us all know and put us out of our 8 bit misery !

Regards

Scott

xyz.scott@virgin.net




@ENDNODE
