Hi Eoghann,

On 17-Nov-98, Eoghann Irving wrote:
> Hi :)
> 
> My program creates a lot of subdirectories while running.  At the
> moment I'm checking if they're already there by using the Exists
> command.
> 
> Unfortunately that seems to cause problems.
> 
> If I go into Dopus after running my program then the directories which
> have been checked (not newly created ones) are locked and I get the
> error
> 
> DOS error code 202 object is in use
> 
> So is there an OS command I can use that would check for the existence
> of a directory?

Yes - the Lock_ command.  Then you can Unlock_ it yourself.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/


--BOUNDARY.1748847632.1
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="FindFile.asc"

; -- must use amigalibs.res
; -- checks for named file or directory
; -- returns -1 (True) if it exists
; -- or 0 (False) if it is not found


Function.b IsThere{filename$}
  *lock=Lock_(&filename$,#ACCESS_READ)   ;attempt to lock it
  If *lock                               ;yes, it is there!
    UnLock_(*lock)                       ;release it
    Function Return -1
  Else                                   ;not found
    Function Return 0
  EndIf
End Function

--BOUNDARY.1748847632.1--




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_160" "Re: Exists problems"
 (envelope-from D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    18 Nov 98 09:57:35 0
From: "David Mcminn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Wed, 18 Nov 1998 09:57:25 -0000
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: Exists problems

On 17 Nov 98, at 18:49, Eoghann Irving wrote:

> My program creates a lot of subdirectories while running.  At the
> moment I'm checking if they're already there by using the Exists
> command.
> 
> Unfortunately that seems to cause problems.

 As do all the other directory type Elmore commands.
 
> If I go into Dopus after running my program then the directories which
> have been checked (not newly created ones) are locked and I get the erro=
r
> 
> DOS error code 202 object is in use
> 
> So is there an OS command I can use that would check for the existence o=
f
> a directory?

 Just a little extension to Curt's program. Use Lock_, Examine and 
Unlock_:

; -- must use amigalibs.res
; -- checks for named file or directory
; -- returns +ve if it exists and is a directory
; -- returns -ve if it exits or if it exists and is a file
; -- or 0 (False) if it is not found


Function.l IsThere{filename$}
  DEFTYPE.FileInfoBlock fib      ; Should actually be long
                                 ; word aligned, don't know
  filetype.l =3D 0                 ; if Blitz does this, but you can
                                 ; use AllocDosObject_ to make sure

  *lock=3DLock_(&filename$,#ACCESS_READ)    ; attempt to lock it
  If *lock                                ; yes, it is there!
    filetype =3D -1                ; Assume it is a file until find out
                                 ; the truth
    If Examine_(*lock,&fib)      ; This part finds out if it is a
                                 ; file or a directory
      filetype =3D fib\fib_DirEntryType     ; dir > 0, file < 0
    End If
    UnLock_ *lock                ; release lock
  EndIf
  Function Return filetype
End Function

; -- a little test
If IsThere{"work:programming.info"}
  NPrint "Oh yes"
End If

NPrint IsThere{"work:oooo"}
NPrint IsThere{"work:disk.info"}
NPrint IsThere{"work:programming"}

ClickMouse
End


|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
  d.mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk ICQ=3D16827694


