Subject: Font widths & rastport


Hi, this is one of those "a few weeks ago someone asked about" posts, so..

A few weeks ago someone asked about finding the width of characters in a
fixed width font. Now I need to do this.

IIRC the OS function TextLength was suggested, pointing it at a single
character string. I've looked at this call and it seems straight forward
enough, but I know nothing about using OS calls. I need to know how to find
the rastport of the window using the font, yes? So how do I do that?

If there's another way of finding the font width I'd be interested in that
too, but I'd still be interested in knowing a bit more about using OS calls
anyway.

Thanks in advance

Mike Child


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_165" "Re: Font widths & rastport"
 (envelope-from D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    12 Nov 98 14:04:46 0
From: "David Mcminn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Thu, 12 Nov 1998 14:04:38 -0000
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: Font widths & rastport

On 12 Nov 98, at 13:12, mike.child@sbu.ac.uk wrote:

 You'll ned amigalibs.res for all this examples.

> IIRC the OS function TextLength was suggested, pointing it at a single
> character string. I've looked at this call and it seems straight forward
> enough, but I know nothing about using OS calls. I need to know how to
> find the rastport of the window using the font, yes? So how do I do that=
?

If you have a Blitz window open, you can load a font and do 
WindowFont #intf to set the font for the currently used window to 
IntuiFont number #intf. To get the rastport address for that window, 
do RastPort(#windownum).

 The call to TextLength will be something like:
LoadFont 0,"fixed.font",8
Window 0,0,0,640,200,$100f,"Test",-1,-1
WindowFont 0
a$=3D"A"
width.w =3D TextLength_(RastPort(0), &a$, 1)
NPrint "The width of the font is ",width
.
.
.
<blah>
.
.

 You can also miss out opening a window, if you go to OS functions, 
as you can create a rastport separately and do this stuff on it 
(obviously not using RastPort(0) to get the address).

i.e.

DEFTYPE.RastPort rp       ; Create our temporary rastport
InitRastPort_ &rp         ; Initialise it (must pass address, hence &)
LoadFont 0,"fixed.font",8 ; Load font and get address of OS bit
*tf.TextFont =3D Peek.l(Addr IntuiFont(0))
If *tf<>0                 ; Make sure we don't do bad things
  SetFont_ &rp, *tf       ; Same as WindowFont 0
  a$=3D"A"
  width.w =3D TextLength_(&rp, &a$, 1)
  NPrint "Width of font =3D ",width
end if

> If there's another way of finding the font width I'd be interested in th=
at
> too, but I'd still be interested in knowing a bit more about using OS
> calls anyway.

 Well, if you look at the TextFont structure of the loaded font, you 
can find out if its proportional. If it is then you can get the 
correct fixed width from the TextFont structure:

LoadFont 0,"fixed.font",8
*tf.TextFont =3D Peek.l(Addr IntuiFont(0))
if (*tf\tf_Flags & #FPF_PROPORTIONAL) =3D 0
    ; Check for the proportional flag being clear 
    ; (not a proportional font)
    NPrint "The width of each character is ",*tf\tf_XSize
else
    NPrint "Font is proportional"
end if


|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
  d.mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk ICQ=3D16827694


