@NODE "Mail_173" "Re: Function Forward"
          Paris Tue, 3 Nov 1998 15:58:23 +0100 (MET)
          Paris Tue, 3 Nov 1998 15:58:22 +0100 (MET)
Date: Tue, 03 Nov 1998 16:00:39 +0100
From: "v.demongodin@wanadoo.fr" <v.demongodin@wanadoo.fr>
X-Accept-Language: fr,en
Subject: Re: Function Forward
Encoding: 7bit

Suppose you have 2 fonctions like that:

    function a1{ parameters .....}

            ...
            res=a2{ other parameters....}
            ...
            function return thomething
    end function

    function a2{parameters...}
            ...
            res=a1{ other parameters...}
            ....
            function return thomthing

    end function

you can rewrite them like that:

    #typea1=0
    #typea2=1

    function a{ type.b, parameters....}

        if type=#typea1
            ;As function a1
           ....
           res=a{typea2, parameters}
           ...

        else
            ;As function a2
             ...
          res=a{typea1,parameters}
        ...

        endif

    end function

You can extend this solution to N functions, replace If
with Select.

Vincent Demongodin.





@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_174" "Re: Function Forward"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Tue, 3 Nov 1998 16:19:32 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Tue, 03 Nov 1998 17:07:44 +0000
Subject: Re: Function Forward

Hi,

>> when using structured programming techniques this problem can
>> never happen. 

> Sorry to dissapoint, but yes it can.  I`ve done a course in Pascal 
> and they recommended you do this.  It`s called recursion and when 
> implemented correctly, is the greatest thing since sliced bread.

Recursion is a different matter altogether and of course there are no
problems using the usual recursion techniques in Blitz.

>  It`s a little difficult to give a brief outline but here goes...
>     user puts in formula eg =SUM(a4:d8,a5,a6*2)
>     function calcy{the string}
>     calcy detects Sum so calls function Sum{}
>     sum{} finds there is a cell reference, so calls calcy to find 
>     what it is  <- my major problem

> Function calcy is a general calculator function ie it can multiply cell 
> refrences, calculate things like 44*22+20 no probs.. It`s quite a 
> smart routine, but it looks like I`m gonna have to split it up to get 
> round this problem.

I guess this is some kind of spreadsheet application so to look at
the problem in a structured way we would look at the 'sheet' as the
main object. The structure of the sheet is made up of many 'cells'.
Each cell is made up of 'data' or 'references to other cells'. I guess
it's not possible for cells to reference themselves without some special
rules/conditions. So, in a structured sence the sheet can contain
one or more "layers" of calculation.

The best way to deal with objects that contain one or more layers
of calculation is to calculate it in one or more pass.

Here's some example code....

sum{} - calculate sum (if all values are available)
calcy{} - calls sum (if needs calculating)

Repeat
  Repeat
    Calcy{}
  Until (all non-calculated cells are passed)
Until (all sheet is calculated)

If you work with the rules that you only calculate the sum of values that
are 'known' then this should work. If the sum requires the values of cells
that contain other sums then they should be left until a later pass. Those
values will be known on a later pass.

here's a similar example.

cell-a = cell-b + 6
cell-b = cell-d / 2
cell-c = cell-a * cell-b
cell-d = 8

Problem... What is cell-c ?

okay so first pass we calculate what we know... cell-a can't be calculated
cell-b can, cell-c can't and cell-d doesn't require calculation. So at the
end of the first pass we know this:

cell-a = cell-b + 6
cell-b = 4
cell-c = cell-a * cell-b
cell-d = 8

Now pass 2.... cell-a can now be calculated, cell-b and cell-d don't need to
be looked at and for example purposes we'll 'pretend' that cell-c can't yet
be calculated. Now we're left with:

cell-a = 10
cell-b = 4
cell-c = cell-a * cell-b
cell-d = 8

So, the final pass would make the cell-a + cell-b calculation and we're left
with:

cell-a = 10
cell-b = 4
cell-c = 40
cell-d = 8

So the answer = 40

There are many ways to achieve this kind of parsing... some would be slow
and
some fast. I'd recomend creating a linked list of cells that need
calculating
and then remove them from the list as they become known. Then when the final
list item is removed you know you've calculated the whole sheet an you've
not wasted time by looking at the same cells over and over.

At the end of this lengthy message I will admit that a recursive approach
would have given you similar results. I'm unsure as to which method would
be faster, it depends how clever the recursion was or how clever the
multi parsing version was. One simple fact remains that sticking with the
legal structured method *usually* makes it faster, easier to follow and easy
to adapt. The multi-pass version would certainly use less stack space which
could be very important if there are MANY cells referencing eachother.

Cheers,

-- 
<- Paul Burkey <-> http://burkey.home.ml.org ->



@ENDNODE
