Hi Paul
Am 10-Nov-98 schrieb Paul Burkey:

> Hi,
> 
>> All worked fine until yesterday. Now I can start it maximal three times.
>> When I then exit with the window`s close gadget the debugger closes,
>> the application too but the program is still running. I need to press
>> "PANIC" in blitz2 to get to the editor back If I enable enforcer I get
>> the following two hits:
> 
>> LONG-READ from 8042BFE0                        PC: 683C5AA2
>> Name: "Background CLI"  CLI: "Blitz2:Dbug/REDDebugger"  Hunk 0000 Offset
>> LONG-READ from 8042BFE0                        PC: 683C5ABE
>> Name: "Background CLI"  CLI: "Blitz2:Dbug/REDDebugger"  Hunk 0000 Offset
> 
> This isn't unusual. The debugger usually causes lots of enforcer hits
> anyway,
> I'm sure it's not an exclusive rule but the job of a debugger is to snoop
> on resources that it doesn't own. If you're program is doing something
> wrong for example loosing track of reserved memory then the debugger
could
> also go wrong. Lets say for example you reserve some memory with blitz
and
> then you free the memory in an 'indirect way'... Blitz still thinks the
> memory is reserved an so the debugger could still be snooping around in
> places you no longer own. This could be due to something like reserving
> some gadgets without freeing them.
> 
>> Now my questions: Anyone had this problem too?
> 
> I've had lots of problems with gui's. Things started going wrong ever
since
> I started using hacks like VisualPrefs. Obviously I'm aware of the
cludges
> that are avaialbe to get around sertain Blitz bugs in connection with
> VisualPrefs
> but I'm sure GUI coding is much harder han it used to be!
yes, if you code a gadtools gui it can be difficult if you want to program
a nice one. There`re alot of things to attend
(fontsensitivity,resizable...)
But if you code a mui gui (just as I did) you don`t have to care about so
much things.....  
> 
>> What does the enforcer hit mean?
> 
> In very basic terms it's reading/writing memory that you don't own or
> memory that has not been reserved by other tasks. Most enforcer hits are
> not simple to track down for example 'Poke.w Rnd(100000),0' could
certainly
> cause a few enforcer hits since it would poke into random areas of mmory.
> However, if you were to force Blitz to free someting that has already
been
> free'd you may also get such enforcer hits.
> 
>> Why does it brings up enforcer hits only the 2nd or 3rd time? Why
>> not the 1st time?
> 
> It's possible that the first run of your code would corrupt memory in
> such a way that Enforcer doesn't catch it. Perhaps your program is
> writing into memory that is owned by another task eg, the Debugger,
> SuperTed or Blitz itself. A typical Amiga would have 40-80 background
> tasks running at any time so there are plenty of places in memory that
> could be open for coruption without alerting Enforcer.
> 
>> How to fix this? I really need a solution! 
>> Please help!! I can`t live with this!!!! Aaargh :))
> 
> I'm afraid this is the one question that can't be answered. I would
> advice you to trim down your code by commenting out as much as
> possible. Then uncomment the code a section at a time until you
> spot the effects of your mystery bug return. You could also try that
> useless suggestion that is never as easy as it seems --> Why not
> remove the most recent bit of code? :)
I think I found the bug that causes the hits and the resulting crash.
It`s in EFMUI Lib. I will send another mail with some source that
causes the crash after this mail.

Thanks for your help!

> 
> Cheers,
> 
Regards
