@NODE "Mail_274" "library size"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Wed, 18 Nov 1998 21:48:28 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 18 Nov 98 21:43:01 +0000
Subject: library size
Encoding: 7bit

Hi folks.

I've been writing a library for blitz that does various things with
chunky graphics. However, the library object (exe) file has grown to
70k at present and just recently I've started experiencing various
crashes when trying to makedeflibs. I looked at makedeflibs.bb2 and it
seems to use strings to input and output libraries. Is there a limit
of 64k to a string? It would seem so. I was also wondering, in what
manner blitz/ted loads in the libraries. Would it load only the first
64k of the library and crop the end off, or would it load the whole
thing if I could get makedeflibs to work with safe memory?

I guess that this being the largest library for blitz (afaik) nobody
has likely encountered this problem before but any info would be
appreciated. I don't particularly want to have to split the library
into two parts.

You may be seeing a `junior' version of this library released for
public use at some point in the near future, although the full library
is for `private' uses only (and there is no documentation yet).

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_275" "Re: library size"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Wed, 18 Nov 1998 20:18:48 -0500
Subject: Re: library size

Hi Paul,

On 18-Nov-98, Paul wrote:
> Hi folks.
> 
> I've been writing a library for blitz that does various things with
> chunky graphics. However, the library object (exe) file has grown to
> 70k at present and just recently I've started experiencing various
> crashes when trying to makedeflibs. I looked at makedeflibs.bb2 and it
> seems to use strings to input and output libraries. Is there a limit
> of 64k to a string? It would seem so. I was also wondering, in what
> manner blitz/ted loads in the libraries. Would it load only the first
> 64k of the library and crop the end off, or would it load the whole
> thing if I could get makedeflibs to work with safe memory?

If you have a deflibs it simply loads that in as-is, I think.
> 
> I guess that this being the largest library for blitz (afaik) nobody
> has likely encountered this problem before but any info would be
> appreciated. I don't particularly want to have to split the library
> into two parts.

>From looking in my amigalibs/ directory, I notice the largest library is
around 68k.  Ones that would have been bigger are split in 2 parts.  I
would guess that this is the size limit, or they wouldn't have bothered
splitting them.  But maybe this limit is only for the makedeflibs program.

Someone pointed out, you don't really need to use a deflibs at all if you
are running from a HD (I assume everybody is these days.)  If you don't
have one, Blitz will use everything in your Blitzlibs drawers.  Have you
tried not using a deflibs?

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_276" "Re: library size"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Thu, 19 Nov 1998 01:33:54 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 19 Nov 98 01:30:21 +0000
Subject: Re: library size
Encoding: 7bit

Anton,
  
>   Have you tried using DeflibMan instead of makedeflibs? It's worth a
> try anyway :-)

You mean blitzlibman? yea I tried that and it crashes when you try to
examine the lib or make a new deflibs. Anyway, not to worry as I've
sorted it out now. I had to modify makedeflibs to use safely reserved
amounts of memory for loading in and writing the libraries, so that
sizes greater than 64k are allowed. As makedeflibs writes library size
to the deflibs file as a longword, it seems to work with blitz/ted
without any problems.

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk



@ENDNODE
