@NODE "Mail_280" "Re: Locking windows"
From: Luca Carminati <toffi@spm.it>
Date: Mon, 30 Nov 1998 23:08:42 -0500
Subject: Re: Locking windows
Encoding: quoted-printable

On 02-Gen-78, l0K! wrote:

>y0 dEWDZ,

>   Does anybody know how to lock a window properly?,. I`ve tried a few
>things,. But none seem to work properly,. Using pointers,tags and stuff,=
=2E I
>can only get a busy pointer up (the gadgets are still selectable,. and t=
he
>window still sizes),. with RTLockWindow and RTUnlockWindow.. i can lock
>them but not unlock them,...

Hi,

you could use the following functions coded by me:

  Function.l LockWindow{Win.l}              ; Window#
    Lock.l=3DAllocMem_(SizeOf .Requester,1)
    If Lock
      Win=3DPeek.l(Addr Window(Win))
      InitRequester_(Lock)
      If Request_(Lock,Win)
        *Exec.Library=3DPeek.l(4)
        If *Exec\lib_Version=3D>39
          Dim tag.TagItem(1)
          tag(0)\ti_Tag=3D#WA_BusyPointer,-1
          tag(1)\ti_Tag=3D#TAG_END
          SetWindowPointerA_ Win,&tag(0)
        EndIf
      Else
        FreeMem_ Lock,SizeOf .Requester
        Lock=3D0
      EndIf
    EndIf
    Function Return Lock
  End Function

  Statement UnlockWindow{Win.l,Lock.l}      ; Window#,Lock
    Win=3DPeek.l(Addr Window(Win))
    *Exec.Library=3DPeek.l(4)
    If *Exec\lib_Version=3D>39
      Delay_ 5
      Dim tag.TagItem(0)
      tag(0)\ti_Tag=3D#TAG_END
      SetWindowPointerA_ Win,&tag(0)
    EndIf
    EndRequest_ Lock,Win
    FreeMem_ Lock,SizeOf .Requester
  End Statement

They use the same syntax of the RT(Un)LockWindow commands. The advantage =
is
that they don't need the reqtools.library. The problem is that on OS2.0
machines the busy pointer doesn't appear (but the window is locked anyway=
).

C ya...


-- =

Best regards,

Luca.

