@NODE "Mail_285" "Mildred"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Mon, 23 Nov 1998 01:59:19 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 23 Nov 98 01:51:47 +0000
Subject: Mildred
Encoding: 7bit

Hi folks.

Mildred is a chunky graphics library that I have been working on for
about a month. It is being used in a few commercial game projects and
I am now bringing it to the public. You will not see the full library
as a public release but instead there will be a `Junior' version,
maintaining a high degree of flexibility and functionality but a
reduced commandset.

The library is not quite in a fit state to release publicly yet, as I
haven't really decided what features to include (or rather exclude)
in the Junior version, but I have begun writing documentation which is
currently available as an on-line manual at:

http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk

The manual is by no means complete but you can take a look at how
things are going so far. The actual library itself should be available
within the week I hope and will continue to be improved over the
course of time. There are currently about 150 tokens in the full
library but I am not sure how many the public library will have yet.

Mildred is intended to be a near complete replacement of all of
blitz's graphics routines, including bitmaps, shapes, cookies,
stencils, various housekeeping routines such as free, addr, use,
autocookie, etc, and also things such as Blit, QBlit, Scroll, and
graphics operations - Plot, Point, BoxF, Cls etc. It is designed to be
a complete system for writing your games (demos, and whatever else) in
chunky graphics format - which is the cutting-edge way to do things on
todays higher end machines. The library has 040+ support as well as a
full implementation of c2p routines and associated commands.

The Scroll and BlockScroll commands have been radically expanded as
have almost all other blit routines and everything is quite highly
optimised. At present, probably all commands needed to write most
games have been coded and everything is of course coded in pure
assembler. Almost all tokens have runtime errorchecking code which can
and should be used to pass valid and safe inputs to the routines.
There is no clipping yet but that may be coming soon. There are also
no load/save routines or example programs which I will be doing
shortly.

In Mildred, pretty much everything you can do to a shape you can do to
a bitmap and vice versa. Bitmaps also have cookies, which I refer to
as stencils. There are a few things I haven't done yet such as buffers
and BBlits but these will hopefully come in time. The public version
will be free of course to use in whatever way you wish but the full
version is being reserved for private use by myself and others in
commercial game projects.

If you have at least a 68030 cpu and either AGA or a graphics card
then you may be interested in using this lib for your projects.

Stay tuned.

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk



