--=_=8<==MD2365B4A62-530DB576==8<=_=
Encoding: 7bit

Hi blitzers.

Here is a new library for your programming pleasure (see attatched
archive). This is not the promised `Junior' version, but instead this
is the FULL library.

It's quite a big one so if you are diet conscious then steer clear.
The library is currently compiled from about 370k of sourcecode into
83k of executable madness, bringing you about 186 new tokens. You will
also need AGA or a graphics-card, and I recommend at least a 68030
cpu (the faster the better).

This is a chunky-graphics library designed to ultimately be the very
foundation of your blitz projects, almost fully replacing and in
many places exceeding the capabilities of the existing blitz
graphics-handling system.

There are two drawbacks. Firstly there are no example programs yet,
and secondly there is not very much documentation yet. I would like
people to send me simple but effective demos and programs using
Mildred, demonstrating its features, so that this can be used as
example programs when Mildred finally grows into a `package'. As far
as documentation is concerned it is available on-line at:

http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk

and this will be the official Mildred support-site where you will be
able to find example sourcecode, advice, tips, documentation and other
related stuff. Only the first chapter of the documentation has been
written so far - Chunky-To-Planar Commands - which covers all of the
c2p-related tokens. Most other tokens can be referenced in the normal
blitz manual to get the jist of what they do although there are of
course a number of new things.

There is runtime-errorchecking code to assist in the use of the
library and to ensure that you are giving it likely and valid
parameters. It does a lot of checking but you should produce your
final executables with runtime errorchecking OFF otherwise it will
have quite an impact on execution speed and can mean a difference of
10 frames per second update. Until you are absolutely sure that your
software will not fall over due to not enough memory or other faults,
you should compile with runtimer error-checking ON and test it
thoroughly. These routines are using only the CPU and there are some
things you can do that would cause a crash (half the fun eh!)

I have tried to make the token names as simple as possible and in
close accordance with the existing blitz tokens that they replace.
There are special 040+ routines for things like blocks and tiles but
be careful that the user has the appropriate cpu. I have fully
implemented a queue system but I have not done buffers yet. I think
buffers are not particularly efficient when doing a lot of graphics
work anyway as it may be faster to just copy a stored background in
its entirity. Stencils are handled a little differently in that a
stencil is attatched to and is an inherant part of a Bitmap object. In
this regard it performs much like a shape's cookie.

There are /extensively/ expanded `scroll' type commands for doing all
sorts of moving of graphics between Bitmaps, Shapes, Cookies and
Stencils. There are also various blits which work with the default 4
blitmodes such as CookieMode, EraseMode, etc. More modes may come in
the future. You can also use a Bitmap's stencil to render an object
behind the protected areas of the bitmap without any need for using
the combination of buffers and ShowStencil that blitz uses. There are
/highly/ optimised tile routines for 16x16 or 32x32 objects.

There is no real clipping at present. Clipping isn't a part of my
chunky-graphics philosophy as I prefer to have a clip-zone around the
edge of the screen, eating more memory but simplifying matters.
Clipping may come in the future, however, and it is already partially
implemented. There are some things that I haven't done yet, some
graphics commands and there is no file loading or saving so you will
currently have to write your own (which is really simple). There is a
screen dissolve routine you can have some fun with. There is a special
origin/handle-based address-offset feature called Wrapping which
assists in engines such as tilescroller and the like, proving a
sliding window in memory. Be VERY careful that you allocate a safe
amount of memory to move into because the library does not check this.
Also note that currently the bitmap's origin or the shape's handle are
ONLY used in this capacity, and do not behave like normal handles.

As I mentioned already there is a full chunky-to-planar system with a
number of associated tokens to simplify matters, including c2pWindow
objects. There are 030 and 040+ c2p routines which can be selected for
use for best performance on the appropriate cpu. The c2p area of the
library is not terribly straightforward, there are some limitations,
but thankfully this is documented already and you should follow the
advice closely (or else! ;-)

Bitmap and Shape objects are internally identical in structure so
most things that can be performed on one can be performed on the
other, allowing easy interfacing between the two. Also there are a lot
of routines for manipulating stencils and cookies, and due to this
flexibility there are many more powerful things possible.

The `SBlit' system is massively enhanced with a variety of scroll
routines to render both the image and the cookie/stencil. There are
also some tile routines that can render to a bitmap, a stencil, and a
background-store bitmap all in one go. You can also perform masked
scrolls, blockscrolls and various other things, including a cut-scroll
which can place something behind the dest bitmap's stencil. You can
also perform masked-blits and masked-scrolls to both bitmaps and
stencils, as well as to shapes and cookies.

There are additional graphics routines to perform Cls, Plot and Point
on all resources, so you can for example plot a pixel to a cookie and
it will be drawn in the correct fashion for a cookie, or clearscreen a
stencil, etc. Some things I haven't done yet such as Box, BoxF,
Line/Draw and polygon type things. You can also perform very quick
horizontal a verticle flips on bitmaps, shapes, stencils and cookies.
No rotation or zooming yet, however.

There are also cludge routines but bear in mind that they will
internally align the address you give them for move16/block
compatibility, by adding 16 to the address and then chopping off the
lower 4 bits. I haven't done CopyBitmap or CopyShape yet although
there are routines to copy the structures which is a kind of cludge.

Generally, keep your chunky data in fastram and make your
contigous-bitplane non-interleaved 256-colour display bitmaps in
chipram. You can double or triple buffer your planar display however
you like because anything you do in the fastram chunky buffer cannot
be seen. There are also routines for handling c2p interlacing features
in single, double, and triple-buffered displays.

All routines in this library begin with a the letter `M', eg MBitmap,
MCls, MQSBlit, etc. I hope that the tokens are mostly
self-explanitory. I have included the quick-help thing (press the HELP
key) to display info in the title bar. Although I am a bit pressed for
space in some commands it may help you out a bit at least to get the
parameters right. Some commands have a few variations in how many
parameters you can pass so in all there are probably more than 200
possible commands to perform.

I hope you enjoy this library and it will continue to be updated and
improved. Please mail me with your comments, suggestions, ideas, and
especialy bug reports. I've been testing things a lot and I think
everything is A-Okay but please let me know if something seems to be
screwed up. Also please mail me if you get stuck figuring out how
various parts of the system work.

Example problems will be on the way in the very near future. I've used
library number 15 but you can of course change it to whatever you find
compatible. Please do not upload the library to Aminet. I don't want
it to go on there until it's more of a `package' with docs and
sourecodes.

This lib is being used in some commercial game projects and I would
like to see the number of projects increase.

Enjoy,

-- 
