@NODE "Mail_297" "More info about the Screen Tags & Double Buffering Problem"
From: Jake Frederick <gonzo@acadia.net>
Date: Tue, 10 Nov 1998 19:32:46 +0500
Subject: More info about the Screen Tags & Double Buffering Problem

On 10-Nov-98, stifter@mira.cz wrote:
>>   I am writing a program that uses screen tags to scroll around on a bitmap
>>that's on a large screen. I am trying to use double  buffering to blit some
>>shapes
>>on top of the scrolling screen but have run into a slight problem. While
>>scrolling the shape jumps back and forth like it's shaking. I think the
>>problem is occuring because when I move the screen it's also moving the
>shapes
>>that are blitted to it making them are move ahead twice as much as they

>I'd say move the bitmap, THEN blit the shapes on the position where
>they are supposed to be. 

Maybe I should have explained it a little better. It's the screen that I'm
moving, not the unseen bitmap. This means that it's always the actual display
that is moved so I can't just blit the shapes in this way without flickering.
-- 
-If the doors of perception were cleansed everything would appear to man as it
truly is, infinite.-



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_298" "Re: More info about the Screen Tags & Double Buffering Problem"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Wed, 11 Nov 1998 16:39:56 -0500
Subject: Re: More info about the Screen Tags & Double Buffering Problem

Hi Jake,

On 10-Nov-98, Jake Frederick wrote:
> On 10-Nov-98, stifter@mira.cz wrote:
>>>   I am writing a program that uses screen tags to scroll around on a
>>> bitmap that's on a large screen. I am trying to use double buffering to
>>> blit some shapes
>>> on top of the scrolling screen but have run into a slight problem.
While
>>> scrolling the shape jumps back and forth like it's shaking. I think the
>>> problem is occuring because when I move the screen it's also moving the
>>>> shapes
>>> that are blitted to it making them are move ahead twice as much as they
> 
>> I'd say move the bitmap, THEN blit the shapes on the position where
>> they are supposed to be. 
> 
> Maybe I should have explained it a little better. It's the screen that
I'm
> moving, not the unseen bitmap. This means that it's always the actual
> display that is moved so I can't just blit the shapes in this way without
> flickering.

It should work OK, I think, if you move the screen after switching the
double-buffered bitmaps.

Also, the shapes movements should always be thought of in relation to the
full bitmap.  In other words, there is no need to do any compensation to
the shapes movements when you scroll the screen.  Rather, the screen should
move when necessary to keep the shape in it's "view", like turning your
head to follow the action at a football game.


                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
