@NODE "Mail_336" "Re: New Amiga Rumours - The Sequel"
Date: Mon, 2 Nov 1998 15:41:56 +0000
From: Adam Lounds <adaml@tcp.net.uk>
Subject: Re: New Amiga Rumours - The Sequel

On Mon, Nov 02, 1998 at 03:23:09PM +0000, Paul said:
> >  The new amiga's are pathetic!
> >  Come on, its bullshit having 32meg of ram, what are we going to do, play a
> > game of pong. You need at least 64 meg before you have an average machine, 128
> > if your serious, and I use 256 for video editing.
> > 
> >  PPC is far too slow and  out of date unless you piggy back the chips, and
> > even then it'll be out of date soon, and the gfx are going to be shit.
> > 
> >  Sorry, but amiga did too little too late.
> 
> Eh up, someone's been sucked into a PC vortex.

32Mb is loads when you run a decent, slimline OS.

Yes, Windows is happy when you get to 64Mb and yes, you'll need more
to do any serious stuff, but that's Windows. You can run a commercial
server with 64Mb if you don't go down the Windows route. 

GFX has hit a bit of a stagnant period at the moment where 2d is 
concerned - 230Mhz RAMDACs are about as fast as you need until you
go above 1200x1600 or something silly. 3d is where all the 
developments are being made. Even a "shit" gfx card (ie 2Mb cirrus
logic for about 20 quid) cuts the mustard (especially vs current
Amiga stuff...) and an intel 740 is only about 40 quid. I can't
see the new Amiga having anything less than this...

Just because windows is a resource hog, doesn't necessarily mean that 
you "need" 64Mb, PII 450 and a Fire GL gfx card or something - look at 
BeOS to see how a PowerPC can fly. Or run linux, solaris or any other
non-windows OS to prove that the slowest part of your intel machine
is the OS it's running.

And whose idea was the registry? Bloody waste of time that is...
</pc rant>
-- 
