Amiga500 with
SF>> 80286 CPU (ouch) ... 286 was '85s top processor (Low cost market
only ...)

SF> But who said that Amigas will have G3's in them ?

The "Mac the Knife" article first referred to at the start of this
thread.  Which has now been debunked by the website that published it,
in which they have apologised because these were misguided
speculations by one person, using second-hand information. This guy
reackoned that the new processor was a G3, he also said that it could
be intel based....but we know for a fact that this isn't true.

SF>> G3 is the present - Amiga must be the future .

SF> Sure, but Amigas aren't gonna be Motorola-based. And even if they
were, what
SF> makes you think that Intel can go ahead of Motorola ? Motorola has
always
SF> been one steap ahead. Motorola always had CPUs that are far more
efficient,
SF> faster, simpler, user-friendlier, smaller, cooler, etc. Intel is
being forced
SF> to develop microprocessors which are based on a 20 year old
architecture and
SF> instructions set, or at least they have to be backward compatible.
Motorola
SF> now only develops truly RISC-based processors with an architecture
barely a
SF> few years old. Current Pentiums are pushing the boundaries of
silicon
SF> technology, and Motorola have a far easier job at bringing out
newer
SF> processors, as they have an excellent base to build on. It all
comes down to
SF> simplicity, efficiency and good design. PCs have never had any of
these, and
SF> they never will. I don't know why AmigaInc are so positive about
not using a
SF> Motorola CPU. Is there anything better out there ?

Unfortunatly tho, intel's processors are the industry standard for
home/office use.  And they are so much cheaper companies can't afford
to use motorolla's processors when compared to intels.  Plus the major
software market is based on x86 processors.

-- 
