@NODE "Mail_347" "Re: New Amiga Rumours - The Sequel"
From: Rick Hodger <rick.thehub@bigfoot.com>
Date: Tue, 03 Nov 1998 12:42:32 +0000
Organization: Corrupted Software
Subject: Re: New Amiga Rumours - The Sequel

I watched as Adam Lounds hammered "Re: New Amiga Rumours - The Sequel"
out on their keyboard...

AL>>  Have you ever Seen the New iMac ? It will piss all over a P2 450
Mhz . Well i
AL>> can't wait to get my One :) . Lets see if PC Quake can Keep up
with iMac Quake
AL>> . What's the Point of Having a Fast CPU when the OS can't keep up
with it . 

AL> Erm...
AL> http://jf.simplenet.com/quakebm/
AL> 3dfx quake.
AL> PC PPro 200  = 43 (only using voodoo1 - voodoo2 up to 107 (!))
AL> Mac 604e @ 232Mhz = 35.3

AL> *I* get 75, or around 45 with a few less "tweaks" (K6-2/350)

AL> Most games on the PC avoid the OS as much as possible. You're
talking
AL> out of your arse.

Actually, you're wrong there.  Most PC games now try to use the OS as
much as possible for compatibility reasons.  If you don't run the
software in an OS friendly way, you can't take advantage of the
built-in retargetable systems like directX and you can only use the
first 640k of RAM (crap PC designers).  If you're going to run a gme
outside of the OS, you have to create all your own code for using
soundcards, and you have to invent some way of using all that extra
memory (most programmers just opt for the DOS4GW method).

AL> Amigas are better than PCs. Fair enough. But don't try to defend 
AL> macs as well. "The OS can't keep up with it" applies even more to
the 
AL> MacOS than windows. 

Macs are pretty damned good, the problem is that they are *too* user
friendly.  I used to work in a PC/Mac/Amiga repair centre, and in the
year I was there, I saw *one* Mac, and it only needed a new power
supply.  There was maybe 20-30 amigas, and hundreads of PC's.

The problem with PC's is that at first they appear to be all nice and
user-friendly....and then you do something it doesn't like.  End of
story, reboot and reinstall Windows.

-- 
