@NODE "Mail_358" "New Amiga rumours I found....."
From: "Gavin Williams" <gavin@micro-media.demon.co.uk>
	<blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
Subject: New Amiga rumours I found.....
Date: Sun, 1 Nov 1998 21:59:43 -0000
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 8bit

Hi all.

Just surfing the net one night and found this on a Mac page. You may find it
interesting. Have a look at
http://macweek.zdnet.com/1998/10/26/op-knife.html for the full story.

Lazarus, come forth!
Speaking of ugly political campaigns: The Knife's spin doctors inform him
that Apple is in a USDA Choice tizzy over an alleged plan by Gateway to
breathe life into Lazarus, the code name for a line of super Amiga boxes
based on the PowerPC G3 and slated to ship in 1999.

Here's the skinny: Some pie-eyed observers insist the G3 silicon runs
AmigaOS 4.0 faster and smoother than it does Mac OS 8.5 or Rhapsody. Adding
insult to injury, Lazarus will ship with a Mac emulation option that will
allegedly run 680x0-based Mac applications faster than a Power Mac. D'oh!

But wait! That's not all: Gateway is also reportedly planning to run AmigaOS
4.0 on Intel processors complete with Mac emulation. Double-d'oh!

Moving right along, AmigaOS 4.0's virtual machine mode, which can boot
another OS and run it natively, should allow Lazarus users to boot BeOS out
of the box and the Mac OS with just a soupçon of additional software. A
deer! A female deer!

Thanks to the tireless efforts of the Knife's grim-faced cadre of special
prosecutors, the Knife has cobbled together a preliminary set of specs for
the CHRP-compliant package: A $1,400 Lazarus package that includes a 15-inch
monitor will pack a 266-MHz G3 chip, an SVGA video port, two Universal
Serial Bus ports, two RS-232C serial ports, one EPP parallel port, built-in
SCSI-3, a 32-speed CD-ROM, a 3-Gbyte hard disk, 16 Mbytes of SDRAM, a V.90
56-Kbps modem, four PCI slots, three Zorro slots and -- dig this! -- a
1.44-Mbyte floppy drive. (An IDE Zip drive will be optional.)

The device's minitower case can be flipped over to do double duty on users'
desktops, and the whole package is reportedly designed to be simple enough
for a Young Republican to use.

Gavin Williams
Amiga 1200, 32mb Ram, 603e 160/040/25, 720mb HD

Join JUST-AMiGA Mailing List: www.onelist.com/subscribe.cgi/just-amiga



@ENDNODE
