@NODE "Mail_377" "OS Friendly routines and stuff :)"
From: Marcel Weber <mw@caverock.net.nz>
Date: Thu, 26 Nov 1998 23:18:16 +1200
Subject: OS Friendly routines and stuff :)

Hi,

I'm currently working on a dynablasters clone in Blitz and I've encountered
a few problems. I would appreciate it if anyone could suggest some
solutions. Especially those who have experience writting OS friendly games
that work on graphics cards.

The game runs in any resolution but it is designed for 640*512 or greater.
The palette is 256 colours and it runs on a screen in amiga mode. The
graphics are all stored in chunky format and drawn to a chunky buffer that
is copied to the planar bitmap under AGA and drawn to graphics cards using
a window and WritePixelArray8_()

1) One problem I have is that I am using a 256 colour palette using
InitPalette and AGAPalRGB for the colours. To attach the palette to the
screen I use "Use Palette". This doesn't work on an ECS machine with a
graphics card. Can anyone suggest another way to do a palette that will
work?

2) WritePixelArray8_() is not that fast on GFX cards. Is there a faster
way?

3) The game only updates the parts of the display that change.
Unfortunately when there is a large explosion much more has to be 
updated and the game slows down. Is there a way to limit the framerate
accurately without chewing up CPU time? Currently I use Ticks and a 
while loop. However Ticks are only accurate to the nearest 50th or 60th
of a second and I need more than that. Any ideas?

4) Is there any way to remove the mouse pointer from a screen without
opening a window on the screen?

5) I am using simplec2p by Paul West (Probably not the latest version). Is
there a faster c2p routine available for Blitz that also supports areas of
smaller size or one that handles areas of less than 32 pixels wide?

Any ideas you can give me would be a great help! :)

-- 

Marcel Weber <mw@caverock.co.nz>
(Xar on #Amiga Undernet/AmigaNet)



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_378" "Re: OS Friendly routines and stuff :)"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Thu, 26 Nov 1998 13:22:03 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <spam@free>
Date: Thu, 26 Nov 1998 13:19:14 +0000
Subject: Re: OS Friendly routines and stuff :)

Hi,

> The game runs in any resolution but it is designed for 640*512 or greater.
> The palette is 256 colours and it runs on a screen in amiga mode. The
> graphics are all stored in chunky format and drawn to a chunky buffer that
> is copied to the planar bitmap under AGA and drawn to graphics cards using
> a window and WritePixelArray8_()

Nice! :)

> 1) One problem I have is that I am using a 256 colour palette using
> InitPalette and AGAPalRGB for the colours. To attach the palette to the
> screen I use "Use Palette". This doesn't work on an ECS machine with a
> graphics card. Can anyone suggest another way to do a palette that will
> work?

In Foundation I use this function (with standard 256 colour palette like
yours...)

Statement UsePalette{scr.w,pal.w}
  LoadRGB32_ ViewPort(scr),Peek.l(Addr Palette(pal))
End Statement

This was added because sometimes screens didn't take the stanard
Use Palette when the screen was "behind". Since adding this function
things are much better.

> 2) WritePixelArray8_() is not that fast on GFX cards. Is there a faster
> way?

Try using cybergraphics.library itself. I've not done it myself but I plan
to use it in the near future to queeze a little more out of gfx-cards. But
I'd say that WritePixelArray8_ isn't *very* slow.. you might be just
experiencing the slowness of Zorro2 bus which is slower than AGA
in some cases. If you don't have Zorro2 then pardon my presumptions,
I'm sure there are faster mthods than writepixelarray8_ but it's not
something I could really notice much on my Zorro2 system :)

> 4) Is there any way to remove the mouse pointer from a screen without
> opening a window on the screen?

There's no real reason not to open a window, it'll do no harm :)

> 5) I am using simplec2p by Paul West (Probably not the latest version). Is
> there a faster c2p routine available for Blitz that also supports areas of
> smaller size or one that handles areas of less than 32 pixels wide?

if you want it to run faster AND you want more flexability then you're
probably asking too much. The reason PWest's c2p routines are so
FAST is due to their 32 bit nature.

Cheers,

-- 
< Paul Burkey - http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk >

"I don't keep donkeys and if I did I certainly wouldn't feed them chips!"
-- Brass Eye



@ENDNODE
