@NODE "Mail_380" "Re: OS Friendly routines and stuff :)"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Thu, 26 Nov 1998 16:17:00 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 26 Nov 98 16:00:40 +0000
Subject: Re: OS Friendly routines and stuff :)
Encoding: 7bit

Marcel,

> I'm currently working on a dynablasters clone in Blitz and I've encountered
> a few problems.

Cool. MasterBlaster is one of the family's favourites.

> 1) One problem I have is that I am using a 256 colour palette using
> InitPalette and AGAPalRGB for the colours. To attach the palette to the
> screen I use "Use Palette". This doesn't work on an ECS machine with a
> graphics card. Can anyone suggest another way to do a palette that will
> work?

I didn't know use palette displayed a palette. I usually use
ShowPalette and its always worked for me althogh I have AGA and Wb3.1.

> 2) WritePixelArray8_() is not that fast on GFX cards. Is there a faster
> way?

Someone has mentioned before of doing a move16 040+ custom copy
routine to a gfx card although I know nothing about how it works. WPA8
is probably okay for speed.
 
> 4) Is there any way to remove the mouse pointer from a screen without
> opening a window on the screen?

Manually position the mouse pointer in the bottom right corner of the
screen and switch off multitasking so that the mouse input handler
stops working? ;-0
 
> 5) I am using simplec2p by Paul West (Probably not the latest version). Is
> there a faster c2p routine available for Blitz that also supports areas of
> smaller size or one that handles areas of less than 32 pixels wide?

The most flexible c2p system so far is part of the Mildred library
recently posted to the list. You can have `windows'. The width still
has to be in multiples of 32 because it works in longwords (and would
be much slower if it didn't). It is also very advisable to output
to coordinates in the planar display that are in multiples of 32
pixels horizontally otherwise the c2p could run at half the rate.

In the library you'll need to use the long version of Mc2pWindow,
supplying the width of the source buffer and the size of the planar
display along with the operation width/height, in order for the
modulo's to work.

The c2p system in mildred has all the features of simplec2p and more,
including interlacing features (albeit that they aren't particularly
attractive). You can gain a few fps by having less flexibility but
there isn't much else you can do in the time you'd save. What cpu do
you have?

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_381" "Re: OS Friendly routines and stuff :)"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Fri, 27 Nov 1998 14:28:41 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Fri, 27 Nov 1998 13:34:24 +0000
Subject: Re: OS Friendly routines and stuff :)

Hi,

>> Statement UsePalette{scr.w,pal.w}
>>  LoadRGB32_ ViewPort(scr),Peek.l(Addr Palette(pal))
>> End Statement

> Thanks. I'll try this, however I think the problem is in the AGAPalRGB
> command or with the use of 256 colour screens... I think I may have to
> construct a palette by poking memory locations.

The AGAPalRGB command should work on any system. It's just
a fancy way of 'poking memory locations'. It's not linked in any way
to the OS or even AGA/ECS.

>> I'd say that WritePixelArray8_ isn't *very* slow.. you might be just
>> experiencing the slowness of Zorro2 bus

> Yes. That would explain it. I think part of the slowdown is having to copy
> the data to a buffer so that only a small area of the display is copied
> rather than the whole display. Although from my tests it seems that a
> graphics card is slower than AGA which seems odd since I am using chunky
> graphics. Maybe its something else I am doing.

chunky or no chunky, the zorro2 bus is slower than AGA so if your
cpu can c2p fast enough you'll see more speed with AGA. Perhaps
some kind of direct gfx-card rendering would narrow the speed gap
and perhaps zorro2 can be pushed faster than AGA but the speed
difference isn't much different.

Cheers,

-- 
< Paul Burkey - http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk >

"The results were disappointing"
-- Fast Show



@ENDNODE
