@NODE "Mail_383" "Re: OS Friendly routines and stuff :)"
From: Marcel Weber <mw@caverock.net.nz>
Date: Sat, 28 Nov 1998 02:13:41 +1200
Subject: Re: OS Friendly routines and stuff :)

Hello Paul

On 27-Nov-98, you wrote:

>> 1) One problem I have is that I am using a 256 colour palette using
>> InitPalette and AGAPalRGB for the colours. To attach the palette to the
>> screen I use "Use Palette". This doesn't work on an ECS machine with a
>> graphics card. Can anyone suggest another way to do a palette that will
>> work?
> 
> In Foundation I use this function (with standard 256 colour palette like
> yours...)
> 
> Statement UsePalette{scr.w,pal.w}
>  LoadRGB32_ ViewPort(scr),Peek.l(Addr Palette(pal))
> End Statement
> 
> This was added because sometimes screens didn't take the stanard
> Use Palette when the screen was "behind". Since adding this function
> things are much better.

Thanks. I'll try this, however I think the problem is in the AGAPalRGB
command or with the use of 256 colour screens... I think I may have to
construct a palette by poking memory locations.

> I'd say that WritePixelArray8_ isn't *very* slow.. you might be just
> experiencing the slowness of Zorro2 bus which is slower than AGA
> in some cases. If you don't have Zorro2 then pardon my presumptions,
> I'm sure there are faster mthods than writepixelarray8_ but it's not
> something I could really notice much on my Zorro2 system :)

Yes. That would explain it. I think part of the slowdown is having to copy
the data to a buffer so that only a small area of the display is copied
rather than the whole display. Although from my tests it seems that a
graphics card is slower than AGA which seems odd since I am using chunky
graphics. Maybe its something else I am doing.

>> 4) Is there any way to remove the mouse pointer from a screen without
>> opening a window on the screen?
> 
> There's no real reason not to open a window, it'll do no harm :)

Well.. Theres an extra 4k of ram used ;)) So I guess you're right it
doesn't
do much harm :)
 
> if you want it to run faster AND you want more flexability then you're
> probably asking too much. The reason PWest's c2p routines are so
> FAST is due to their 32 bit nature.

Hmmm.. Maybe I am asking too much... Still I'd be happy with same speed and
more flexibility or just faster speed ;)

-- 

Marcel Weber <mw@caverock.co.nz>
(Xar on Amiga Undernet/AmigaNet)



@ENDNODE
