@NODE "Mail_386" "Re: OS Friendly routines and stuff :)"
 (envelope-from FlameDuck@usa.net)
 (envelope-from FlameDuck@usa.net)
From: Mikkel =?iso-8859-1?Q?L=F8kke?= <FlameDuck@usa.net>
Date: Sat, 28 Nov 1998 16:21:36 +0200
Organization: A97
Subject: Re: OS Friendly routines and stuff :)
Encoding: quoted-printable

Hello Marcel.

On 26-Nov-98, Marcel Weber wrote:

Here is my 2 cents worth.

> 1) One problem I have is that I am using a 256 colour palette using
> InitPalette and AGAPalRGB for the colours. To attach the palette to the=

> screen I use "Use Palette". This doesn't work on an ECS machine with a
> graphics card. Can anyone suggest another way to do a palette that will=

> work?

Hrmmm, dunno if this works, but how about just loading the palette, and t=
hen
doing a showpalette ? You should allways start your programs with the
NewPaletteMode On command. This way Use Palette works the way it's SUPPOS=
ED
to. :o) =


> 2) WritePixelArray8_() is not that fast on GFX cards. Is there a faster=

> way?

Not very likely. Unless you use the RTGMaster, Cybergraphics or P96
libraries. =


> 3) The game only updates the parts of the display that change.
> Unfortunately when there is a large explosion much more has to be =

> updated and the game slows down. Is there a way to limit the framerate
> accurately without chewing up CPU time? Currently I use Ticks and a =

> while loop. However Ticks are only accurate to the nearest 50th or 60th=

> of a second and I need more than that. Any ideas?

First of, WHY would you need more than 1/50th of a second ? And from what=
 I
can read you are chewing up tons of CPU time. The "professinal" way of
doing it is to do different parts of your code each frame. This way your
game WON'T go at 50fps (Not a huge problem, since the eye cannot detect
more than 12-13) but the spare time can be used for all kinds of effects.=
 I
can recomend the WaitTOF_ command, which is an OS friendly counterpart to=

VWAit, which doesn't cause CPU overhead.

> 4) Is there any way to remove the mouse pointer from a screen without
> opening a window on the screen?

Not in a system friendly way. Just open a window, it won't make any
difference.


Regards
-- =

