Subject: Re: PCs Breaa

Hello Rick

On 06-nov-98, Rick Hodger wrote:

> Now, if you've got a P2-400 that's is using a hard-disk for ALL it's
> storage, volitile and non-volitile.  Not only will that hard-disk be
> going beserk all the time, but it's going to break down much faster
> than normal, but the CPU is going to be constantly waiting on data to
> arrive from the hard-disk.  And if you use the hard-disk for volitile
> stuff, that hard-disk is going to fill up with crap quicker than you
> can say "intel", and that's going to been more maintenance yet again.

> Sorry, but building a computer the relies completely on it's hard-disk
> for storage is a completely stupid idea.  If and when they invent a
> mass-storage device that does involve mechanical parts....then you
> could consider it.

> Oh, and how exactly will you boot this machine with no RAM?  It needs
> to run the BIOS before it can find the hard-disk and determine it's
> paramters, with no volitle storage where exactly is it going to put
> the parameters?  And it can't perform any pre-boot hardware checks,
> which means that if anything goes wrong /anywhere/ on that PC, it'll
> not boot, no error message, nothing.

> PS - IBM is the only company who reackon they *might* be able to make
> a terrabyte drive, but it'll not be for a while yet and they don't
> know how reliable it'll be.

Memory is very cheap and extremely efficient these days. Now that they can
make FETs (transistors) that are only a couple of thousand atoms(!) long,
memory is becoming the most efficient storage media today. If I recall
correctly, they've made a gigabyte RAM chip a while ago... and the size of it
is much smaller than a hard-drive, even if you put 50 of them together on a
board, it'll still be smaller than a hard-drive, use less power, no noise,
etc. However, I think that optical storage media is going to be much cheaper
than even memory. Look at a DVD disc for instance, being able to store about
4 GB of data on a single layer.

Regards
-- 
Stephen



