 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Sun, 22 Nov 1998 19:33:10 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Sun, 22 Nov 1998 19:12:28 +0000
Subject: Re: Planar 2 Chunky

Hi,

>> I need to convert an 8bit planar bitmap to chunky. So far I'm
>> using a basic Poke() and Point() method that converts a planar
>> bitmap of 640x480 in less than 2 seconds (89 ticks) on my 040.
>> This conversion isn't required in a real-time situation so 2
>> seconds isn't too bad but if anyone has a faster Point() command
>> or a faster method altogether let me know!

>    First, you should use the NPoke() routine which is about 20% faster
> than the original Poke routine or better, use this little tricks to poke
> into memory:

I tried NPoke() but it was about 1% slower. Perhaps this is a difference
based on different cpu's and/or different versions of blitz.

>    NewType .byte   ;  
>        byte.b           ; Change to the value to poke 
>    End NewType    ;
>    Deftype .byte *a
>    *a = *ChunkyBuffer
>    *a\byte = YourValueToPoke : *a+1 ; Increase your position of 1
>    
>    This method is even faster than the standard NPoke() routine.

Now this one looks interesting. I'll just test it.....

Yes!! It's now 6% faster! Almost down to 80 'ticks' for a 640x480 bitmap.

BTW, I'm poking the pixels 4 at a time with this:-

*long\long= (Point(x,y) LSL 24)  +  (Point(x+1,y) LSL 16)  --->
      + (Point(x+2,y) LSL 8) + Point(xx+3,yy)

So this builds up a LONG using 4 Point() commands.

I don't know if anyone can suggest another way to speed this up
but I think I should now look at some p2c code on Aminet as
suggested by Sami and PWest.

Cheers,

-- 
< Paul Burkey - http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk >

