On the subject, I just thought i'd pass along the results of some
experiments I'd done.  This is on an NTSC AGA 060 x 50 - maybe different
results on other processors.

Also note that I used the Blitz Chunky commands (the ones built into
AcidLibs, not any of the 3rd party ones) since this has a command
"ChunkyToBitmap" that is faster than using WritePixelArray8_ ...

Anyway, I tried saving a 640 x 400 x 256 colour picture as both standard
ILBM, and as 8 bit chunky.

Then, again using standard Blitz commands, I reloaded each to a Bitmap, t=
hen
BitMapToWindow'd it to my window.  (In the case of the chunky, I of cours=
e
reloaded it as a Chunky, then used ChunkyToBitmap)

Results (from start of disk load until pic presented in window):  =


Standard ILBM   134 ticks
Chunky           88 ticks (includes time needed to convert to planar
bitmap)

So as you can see, it would not only completely eliminate the overhead of=

the planar to chunky conversion (as well as the chip ram needed), but wou=
ld
even be faster loading for normal planar use of the graphics!  The only
drawback is the larger disk file size of the chunky - my example pic was
146720 as ILBM, 256032 as chunky. =



                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




