Subject: Re: Planar 2 Chunky

> So as you can see, it would not only completely eliminate the overhead o=
f
> the planar to chunky conversion (as well as the chip ram needed), but
> would even be faster loading for normal planar use of the graphics!  The
> only drawback is the larger disk file size of the chunky - my example pi=
c
> was 146720 as ILBM, 256032 as chunky. 

 I assume that your chunky saved bitmap has no type of 
encoding/compression and that your ILBM is RLE compressed. That along 
with the fact that ILBM pics are effectively saved as chunky (ooh, 
better not be wrong) as they have bunches of <Run length>,<Colour 
register>. As the colour register is used, it has to be plotted or 
drawn as a line onto the bitmaps rather than just read into the 
correct memory location. Perhaps it would be an idea to try to load 
ILBMs as chunky, i.e. read the data straight into memory??


|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
  d.mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk ICQ=3D16827694


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_412" "Re: Planar 2 Chunky"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Tue, 24 Nov 1998 06:01:03 -0500
Subject: Re: Planar 2 Chunky

Hi David

On 24-Nov-98, David Mcminn wrote:
>> So as you can see, it would not only completely eliminate the overhead
of
>> the planar to chunky conversion (as well as the chip ram needed), but
>> would even be faster loading for normal planar use of the graphics!  The
>> only drawback is the larger disk file size of the chunky - my example
pic
>> was 146720 as ILBM, 256032 as chunky. 
> 
> I assume that your chunky saved bitmap has no type of 
> encoding/compression and that your ILBM is RLE compressed.

I think this is right, as I used the standard Blitz SaveBitmap command for
the ILBM picture.

And, of course there are chunky compression formats available such as .png
which could be used to reduce the file size (and increase the loading time)


>That along 
> with the fact that ILBM pics are effectively saved as chunky (ooh, 
> better not be wrong) as they have bunches of <Run length>,<Colour 
> register>. As the colour register is used, it has to be plotted or 
> drawn as a line onto the bitmaps rather than just read into the 
> correct memory location. Perhaps it would be an idea to try to load 
> ILBMs as chunky, i.e. read the data straight into memory??

Well, that's how Amiga Basic used to do it (those ACBM pics are really just
uncompressed ILBM) but since normal ILBM's are compressed, this wouldn't
work without some sort of decompression code...   Errr, like what's used by
the LoadBitMap command...

I had looked into this once, and found that ILBM is not actually saved as
"chunky" as I was hoping, but rather the bitplanes themselves are
compressed individually.
It looks like rather a tangled mess to unravel...  

Anyway the original question was on the fastest way to load and convert
planar graphics to chunky.  I was just pointing out that the fastest way
for GFX card or standard systems alike was to do the reverse, load as
chunky and then convert it to planar if necessary (for non-GFX card
systems)

