@NODE "Mail_413" "Re: Planar 2 Chunky"
From: Sami =?iso-8859-1?Q?N=E4=E4t=E4nen?= <sami.naatanen@dlc.fi>
Date: Tue, 24 Nov 1998 22:18:35 +0200
Organization: Diverse
Subject: Re: Planar 2 Chunky
Encoding: quoted-printable

On 24-Nov-98, David Mcminn wrote:
> > So as you can see, it would not only completely eliminate the overhea=
d of
> > the planar to chunky conversion (as well as the chip ram needed), but=

> > would even be faster loading for normal planar use of the graphics!  =
The
> > only drawback is the larger disk file size of the chunky - my example=
 pic
> > was 146720 as ILBM, 256032 as chunky. =


>  I assume that your chunky saved bitmap has no type of =

> encoding/compression and that your ILBM is RLE compressed. That along =

> with the fact that ILBM pics are effectively saved as chunky (ooh, =

> better not be wrong) as they have bunches of <Run length>,<Colour =

> register>. As the colour register is used, it has to be plotted or =

> drawn as a line onto the bitmaps rather than just read into the =

> correct memory location. Perhaps it would be an idea to try to load =

> ILBMs as chunky, i.e. read the data straight into memory??


Well in fact the RLE encoding works like this:

read byte to n. if n is lower than zero (-1 - -128), then you will write
the next neg n bytes with the byte which is the next byte from the RLE
data. if the n is positive you will write the next n bytes by just copyin=
g
the n bytes from the RLE data to the destination. Then you will read the
next byte to n and start comparing again and again and ... until EOF. :)

So quite easy and fast.

