@NODE "Mail_419" "Planar to Chunky"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Sat, 28 Nov 1998 05:11:09 +0000
From: "Paul" <paulwest@stationone.demon.co.uk>
Organization: private
Date: 28 Nov 98 05:04:24 +0000
Subject: Planar to Chunky
Encoding: 7bit

Hi.

I have taken Mildred to version 1.14 with the addition of two
planar-to-chunky related commands. They're pretty fast! The commands
are:

MPlanar16ToBitmap
MPlanar16ToShape

There is a short and a long version. The short version requires two
parameters:

BitmapNum.w,Planar.l

or

ShapeNum.w,Planar.l

You have to create a chunky shape or bitmap first with MShape or
MBitmap. In the short version, the size of the shape/bitmap must be
exactly the same as the size of the planar bitmap.

In the long version there are four *additional* parameters:

OpWidth.w,OpHeight.w,PlanarWidth.w,PlanarHeight.w

These allow you to specify an area that is possibly smaller than the
planar bitmap and smaller than the chunky bitmap/shape.

Your planar data should be non-interleaved and the bitplanes should be
contiguous. There should not be any modulo in the planar bitmap data.
If there is it will be ignored.

The width of the operation and the width of the planar bitmap should
be multiples of 16 pixels. You are allowed to position the planar
source address wherever you like, depicting the topleft corner of the
source data. The data will be converted and placed into the specified
shape or bitmap at coordinates 0,0.

On my 040/25, a conversion of 320x240 takes 9/50th's, and a conversion
of 640x480 takes 36/50ths, which I think is about 3-4 times faster
than using a Point&Poke method.

Try to have your planar data in fastram, such as loading in a picture
to a bitmap cludged onto fastram memory. This helps with the speed a
bit. Also the time quoted above is in blitz mode with no bitplanes, as
the dma-fetch for the display has an impact on conversion speed even
when not converting from chipram. I think you should get 20-25/50ths
on an 040/40 and probably 10-15 on an 060/50, for 640x480.

The routine is highly optimised and was a nightmare to get working.
Planar data is read only once and 8 bitplanes are handled at a time,
reading a word from each. These words convert to 16 pixels of chunky
data which are output in longwords only once, so there is minimal
memory access. Even so, the actual computation to do the conversion
takes up far more of the time than the input or output of data. I
don't think it can be optimised any further.

Mildred v1.14 is uploaded to the support site at:

http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk 

and is the version that contains the implemented planar-to-chunky
commands.

-- 
Paul.

IRC: #amiga, Dalnet: #blitz
WWW: http://www.stationone.demon.co.uk
E-M: paul@stationone.demon.co.uk



