@NODE "Mail_424" "PPC C2P"
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Sun, 22 Nov 1998 13:05:06 +1200
Subject: PPC C2P

  I finally got QuakePPC- Well Click-Boom weren't going to put out a PPC
version so I bought a PC copy- I wanted it be running at a decent frame
rate- then after I found QuakePPC ...

  Anyway, here's something from it's docs you might be interested in:

Chunky2planar (AGA) or WPA8 (gfx cards) runs on 68k side in parallel
with the ppc, so ppc can go on calculating next frame. This means the
speed is quite the same on AGA and on gfx cards, but on AGA it uses
quite a lot of cpu on 68060.

  It only seems to use about 45% CPU on the 040/25. Interesting- huh!
For those interested, it runs on (AGA) about 25fps on 320*256, and at
about 10fps at 320*512 (that's a laced screen)- and Paul you're right,
interlaced does look better than 640*256! I suppose it's because pixels
are rectangular.  

 Also, the lastest version runs multi-player through the internet, so
here are some observations, now I've finally had a chance to do some
multiplayer gaming- it's about bloody time!! :)
   Quake uses Client-Server routines for communication (I assume it does
the same for someone acting as Server from their machine, not just a
dedicated (or should that be deadicated :) Server at an ISP), so Paul B,
you were right in the end- damn you!! :-)
  I still want to experiment with Peer To Peer and see if it's will work
gameplay-wise - the bigger the lags the more problem it will cause I
think, as the position you are on your screen and what the other players
will see will diverge- but it's offset by the point that it halves the
lag times. Also if the Server is just hosted on someones computer,
rather than on a Server permanently connected through the net, messages
have to go through 4 modems, which would cause huge lags (unless 56k
modems are much faster than older ones). 
  It seems to use about 1.2M/hour (4 players, 10fps), and about
1.5M/hour (12 players), so my 14400 modem had no problem with that.
Also,faster framerates will cause more traffic to be sent by you. Does
anyone get different data rates than these?

  Ps: I've put in the disconnect routines in UDP_Chat and tidied up the
code a bit, I've got to do some more before I put this version on the
net, so if you want it, E-Mail me directly, as I'll be a bit busy with
Xmas etc. 
 
-- 
        Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz> ICQ #15349462 
      A500,DF1:,0.5MC,8.5MF,60HDD,WB3.1 &1.3/2.0 
    A1200 WB3.0,25/040,200/PPC,CD-Rom- using the 500-need IDE buffer :-/
