same way.




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_441" "Re: Problem with Paul's AHI example"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Thu, 26 Nov 1998 13:22:01 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <spam@free>
Date: Thu, 26 Nov 1998 13:13:57 +0000
Subject: Re: Problem with Paul's AHI example

Hi,

> Very confused =[
> In the AHISetup{} statement the #AHI_AllocAudioA_# function sets *actrl to
> null every time =[

Perhaps your audio hardware is already allocated by something else or
maybe AHI really does need a *little* fast mem to work in.

> I noticed I only have around 28k contiguous free fast mem...  Could
> that be it?

28k of fast mem? How much do you normaly have and where did it all go? :)

> I reduced #MAX_SAMPS to 2 and set AHI's Audio Mode to 8bit mono,
4000khz...
> in the hope of reducing the size of any needed AHIbuffer, but still no
> good. AHI _can_ use chip, too, if it's out of fast, right?

AHI does use chip mem for samples but perhaps it need some
workspace in fast mem for internal purposes (mix tables etc..)

> 1) Am I doing something wrong?  (I havn't edited the sources)

It's almost ertainly a problem with your setup, perhaps memory, pehaps
audio channels not allocated, perhaps ahi's paula drivers aren't working,
perhaps you're using 68000 (probably not..). I'd suggest you play around
with other AHI apps to be sure AHI actually works for you.

> 2) How much contiguous fast mem does AHI #NEED# to set itself up?

probably not much but 28k of free fast mem sounds like a joke ;)

> 3) How much mem gets eaten up by AHI for each sample info?  
>      (#MAX_SAMPS)

Again, probably not much and I1d say that most (if not all) of AHI's
memory allocation would work in chip ram, however it could also be
very choosy about where it's mixing work is done.

Cheers,

-- 
< Paul Burkey - http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk >

"Fondled by a nonce."
-- Brass Eye




@ENDNODE
