@NODE "Mail_508" "Serial question"
    5 Nov 98 14:59:24 +0200 (EET)
From: "Ott Aaloe" <ott@mail.lbi.ee>
Organization: Arvutisalong Enter
Date: Thu, 5 Nov 1998 14:59:11 +0300 (EETDST)
encoding: 7BIT
Subject: Serial question

Hi!

I've done a small terminal program and everyhing works fine...I found
Acid demo code and built mine over it...ok...the problem is it eats
a lot cpu time...as the main loop looks something like this:

while in
	b=readserial(0)
	if b<>0 then dosmething else continuelooping
wend

well...not a nice way to do things...as it slows down other 
processes running. And I can't add vwait to loop either as 
I miss some data that comes from serial...
So what would be a solution. I suppose I should change the base 
serial reader idea completely (perhaps using some interrupts) or 
what?
 

*** Ott (ott@lbi.ee)

 


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_509" "Re: Serial question"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Thu, 5 Nov 1998 14:14:33 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Thu, 05 Nov 1998 14:55:24 +0000
Subject: Re: Serial question

Hi,

> I've done a small terminal program and everyhing works fine...I found
> Acid demo code and built mine over it...ok...the problem is it eats
> a lot cpu time...as the main loop looks something like this:

> while in
>     b=readserial(0)
>     if b<>0 then dosmething else continuelooping
> wend

I've never used the serial commands myself so I'm not aware of
the best usage. I can however spot a way to improve the above
code by putting a Delay inside the loop eg 'Delay_ 1'. If the readserial
function returns something. You would obviously need to empty the
read buffer before returning to the delayed loop. Then simply
increase the size of the Delay depending on how instant you
need to respond to the serial input.

> well...not a nice way to do things...as it slows down other 
> processes running. And I can't add vwait to loop either as 
> I miss some data that comes from serial...

hmm, does serial data disapear if you don't read it? I can't imagine
that being the case although I'm always happy to be corrected :)

> So what would be a solution. I suppose I should change the base 
> serial reader idea completely (perhaps using some interrupts) or 
> what?

Maybe you could use the 'serial receive buffer' interupt or maybe
Acids serial commands offer 'serial Query' support which is used
to get the status of the serial port and the number of bytes in the
read buffer. Perhaps you could consider using the exec.library
to control the serial port yourself. The options are endless.....

Cheers,

-- 
< Paul Burkey - burkey.home.ml.org >

