@NODE "Mail_511" "Re: Serial question"
From: Rick Hodger <rick.thehub@bigfoot.com>
Date: Fri, 06 Nov 1998 18:41:01 +0000
Organization: Corrupted Software
Subject: Re: Serial question

I watched as Paul Burkey hammered "Re: Serial question" out on their
keyboard...

PB> I've never used the serial commands myself so I'm not aware of
PB> the best usage. I can however spot a way to improve the above
PB> code by putting a Delay inside the loop eg 'Delay_ 1'. If the
readserial
PB> function returns something. You would obviously need to empty the
PB> read buffer before returning to the delayed loop. Then simply
PB> increase the size of the Delay depending on how instant you
PB> need to respond to the serial input.

Yup, that'll slow it down a bit.

PB>> well...not a nice way to do things...as it slows down other 
PB>> processes running. And I can't add vwait to loop either as 
PB>> I miss some data that comes from serial...

Urm, you shouldn't be losing data from the serial port as it has a
buffer that fills up and waits to be emptied before going further.  If
stuff is disappearing there's something wrong with your miggy!

PB> hmm, does serial data disapear if you don't read it? I can't
imagine
PB> that being the case although I'm always happy to be corrected :)

PB>> So what would be a solution. I suppose I should change the base 
PB>> serial reader idea completely (perhaps using some interrupts) or 
PB>> what?

You could try the "ReadSerialString" command, that'll read the entire
string in for you and make it readable, then just change the "If b<>0
then whatever" to "If b$<>"" then whatever"

-- 
