@NODE "Mail_535" "Re: Sort"
 (envelope-from D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    9 Nov 98 09:41:10 0
From: "David Mcminn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Mon, 9 Nov 1998 09:41:08 -0000
Subject: Re: Sort


--Message-Boundary-18171
encoding: Quoted-printable
Content-description: Mail message body

On 8 Nov 98, at 14:01, Bippy M wrote:

> Hello Blitzee's,
> 
> Well I sorted out the format probs with my Msg Stats prog.. but now I ha=
ve
> a problem sorting the data...
> 
> Is there a way of linking a name and a value  (i.e Bippy M   34)
> which are in 2 different arrays (or maybe a newtype)
> 
> and then sorting it all so the person with the highest number is at the
> top etc...

 You'd probably have to use a newtype anyway you did it (unless 
you're some kind of masochist). The simplest way would be to use a 
newtype which holds the name and the number and have an array of 
them. The more complex (and verging on ridiculus) way would be to use 
a newtype, which holds the name and the the index into the number 
array.

 I've attached an archive which is probably more use to other people 
on the list (ignore the makepeeps file, it doesn't do what the 
sorted2 program wants). Basically this shouws how to use sorted index 
arrays - an easy way of sorting many fields of data on more than one 
field at the same time. You keep your data items in any order then 
use another array or list for each field you want to sort on - this 
new array stores the indexes into the data array or pointers to the 
list items as they would appear if they were sorted. Then when you 
want to use them as sorted, access them by finding out the 
index/address first. This method doesn't really work with Blitz type 
lists, as they are the root of all evil!


