@NODE "Mail_538" "Re: Sound sample rates"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sun, 22 Nov 1998 18:06:50 -0500
Subject: Re: Sound sample rates

Hi,

On 22-Nov-98, Paul Burkey wrote:
> Hi,
> 
>> How do you work out the period from the samplerate you want? I guess
it`s
>> k/period=samplerate where k is the number I don`t know... Thanks for
>> reading!
> 
> Try something like $369E30/period
> 
> Don't ask me where that figure came from though :)

Here is a formula for samples that I've used. I'm not sure exactly what you
are looking for (I don't know what samplerate is) but maybe the information
is in here somewhere?

And I'm not sure exactly how I go this either, but it does work  ;)


  period=Peek.w(Addr Sound (0)+4)                 ;get the period from
sound
object
  lngth.l=(Peek.w(Addr Sound (0)+6) AND $FFFF)*2  ;get the length from
sound
object
  frequency.f = 3579440/period                    ;convert to true
frequency


                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_539" "Re: Sound sample rates"
Date: Mon, 23 Nov 1998 21:39:37 +1300
From: Julian Kinraid <jkinraid@clear.net.nz>
X-Accept-Language: en-GB,en
Subject: Re: Sound sample rates
Encoding: 7bit

Hello,

> >> How do you work out the period from the samplerate you want? I guess
> it`s
> >> k/period=samplerate where k is the number I don`t know... Thanks for
> >> reading!
> >
> > Try something like $369E30/period
> >
> > Don't ask me where that figure came from though :)
> 
> Here is a formula for samples that I've used. I'm not sure exactly what you
> are looking for (I don't know what samplerate is) but maybe the information
> is in here somewhere?
> 
> And I'm not sure exactly how I go this either, but it does work  ;)
> 
>   period=Peek.w(Addr Sound (0)+4)                 ;get the period from
> sound
> object
>   lngth.l=(Peek.w(Addr Sound (0)+6) AND $FFFF)*2  ;get the length from
> sound
> object
>   frequency.f = 3579440/period                    ;convert to true
> frequency

I think the samplerate is the number of 'samples' to play per second...
or something like that, I really don't know what I'm talking about :)  
The way I found out that magic number (and I think I told Paul), was by
looking at the loadsound command with a asm monitor.  When Blitz loads
in an 8svx sample, it takes the number 3579440 and divides that by the
frequency (stored in the sample header) to get the period.  The magic
number might have something to do with PAL/NTSC timings.  There are two
similar numbers stored somewhere in the amiga includes.

--
Julian Kinraid



@ENDNODE
