On 23-Nov-98, Curt Esser wrote:
> Hi,

> On 22-Nov-98, Paul Burkey wrote:
> > Hi,
> > =

> >> How do you work out the period from the samplerate you want? I guess=

> it`s
> >> k/period=3Dsamplerate where k is the number I don`t know... Thanks f=
or
> >> reading!
> > =

> > Try something like $369E30/period
> > =

> > Don't ask me where that figure came from though :)

> Here is a formula for samples that I've used. I'm not sure exactly what=
 you
> are looking for (I don't know what samplerate is) but maybe the informa=
tion
> is in here somewhere?

> And I'm not sure exactly how I go this either, but it does work  ;)


>   period=3DPeek.w(Addr Sound (0)+4)                 ;get the period fro=
m
> sound
> object
>   lngth.l=3D(Peek.w(Addr Sound (0)+6) AND $FFFF)*2  ;get the length fro=
m
> sound
> object
>   frequency.f =3D 3579440/period                    ;convert to true
> frequency

To any interested ones here is the explanation.

Well this magic number is inner clock speed and it differs a litlebit fro=
m
PAL to NTSC machine so you should check this out and use the apropriate
value for the calculation. The value can be foun from the execbase, but I=

can't remember the position now. I think it can be found from the exec
includes though.

So why you have to use the period value and not the frecuency?
Well Paula will get an clock cycle from the inner clock and it will use
this for sound synchronization. So to achieve certain frecuency you need =
now the inner clock speed and the period which can achieved by dividing t=
he
clock speed by the sample frecuency.

All this info is available from the Rom Kernel Hardware Reference Manual.=


