@NODE "Mail_544" "Re: sound samples"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Wed, 18 Nov 1998 04:43:16 -0500
Subject: Re: sound samples

Hi,

On 17-Nov-98, James L Boyd wrote:
> Rick Hodger churned out *this* drivel :
> 
>> How exactly do you find the length of a sample already loaded into
>> memory? I've tried using the .sound type with the \_length bit.....but
>> if I load a sample of around 150k, it reports it as being a mere 23k. 
> 
> If I remember rightly, the OS as standard only allows samples
> up to 128k (0-127). Because your sample's 150k, you get 150-127 (unsigned
> bytes
> or something) which = 23k...
> 
> I think you've got to do things your own way if you want more than
128k...
> though I may be wrong...
> 
> I am, aren't I? :)

No, you're right - Blitz (and the OS) can only play from memory a sample
128k or less.

If you want to use something longer, you'll have to play it from disk (or
load the file into RAM: and diskplay it from there) or use your own
double-buffered playing routine.

Here is how I find a sample's length (the length of the sample data only):

lngth.l=(Peek.w(Addr Sound (0)+6) AND $FFFF)*2  ;get the length from sound
object

Later...

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_545" "Re: SoundFx"
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby.lnk@ispi.net>
Date: Sun, 29 Nov 1998 10:20:31 +0500
Subject: Re: SoundFx

On 29-Nov-98, Dave flashed:
>Hi,

>Anyone know how to program the sound of an engine?
>I want the sound to change with different revs like in
>skidmark.

  Believe it or not, almost any very short sound sample looped
repeatedly will sound simulsr to an engine.  A short explosion or
gun sound makes a quite convincing unmuffled engine sound as in
an aircraft or racecar.  Use softer sounds such as a 'swish' or
wind noise for highly restricted exhaust systems such as a passenger
car.  Use low frequency musical instrument samples such as an organ
for 'tuned exhaust' effects.  If you wish to program the sounds
from scratch instead of playing sound samples then program a single
tone such as the above and repeat it at varying frequencys.
  I once made a very convincing helecopter sound including engine
noise and 'blade slap' by playing a plucked guitar sample backwards.
Experiment around with different looped sounds and you will soon
have your solution.


cacha later,

-- 
Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)




@ENDNODE
