@NODE "Mail_551" "Re: Source code (was DefLibs... yet again)"
 (envelope-from D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    19 Nov 98 09:20:42 0
From: "David Mcminn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Thu, 19 Nov 1998 09:20:31 -0000
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: Source code (was DefLibs... yet again)

On 18 Nov 98, at 20:37, James L Boyd wrote:

> Absolutely right - even if you don't have that library, you can still se=
e
> what the command is supposed to be...


And its always nice to be told what other libs you may need at the 
top of your program (saves having to send a message to the list 
saying "What lib does SuperDuperBlitXY come from?").
 
> I always upload stuff to Aminet in both formats (cos if people can load
> the .bb2 file, they don't have to set up the Compiler Options themselves=
> as long as the .xtra file's in there too, but the ASCII's there to fall
> back

 Eh? Why not just save the the source in ASCII as blah.bb2, and put 
the compiler options in there as well? Sure it'll take longer to load 
the program the first time (when Blitz tokenises it) but this won't 
matter if:
  1) The source is short
  2) You have a good processor, and you should for doing development
  3) You save the program after tokenisation, thus not needing to do 
it again

 Even better, you could include your entire Blitzlibs: directory in 
the archive, then everyone will be sure to have the same development 
material as you ;)


