@NODE "Mail_561" "Re: Straight lines"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Wed, 25 Nov 1998 12:11:04 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Wed, 25 Nov 1998 12:08:40 +0000
Subject: Re: Straight lines

Hi,

> Does anyone know the basic principle (code) for a sprite to move in a 
> *direct* straight line from one point to another at a *constant* speed?
> (I say `basic principle' because Blitz isn't the language I'm currently
> using for my programming).

I'd recomend Bresenham's Line Algorithm which is shown here
in the folowing non language specific code....

I've used this algorithm in many projects including my recent graphics
rewrite for Foundation as well as other code in C so it seems to work
well with any language.

;---------------------------------

(Given A(x1,y1) and B(x2,y2) and that the line is from A to B)

X <-- x1
Y <-- y1

DeltaX <-- x2 - x1
DeltaY <-- y2 - y1

IF DeltaX < 0
    XChange <-- -1
    DeltaX = -DeltaX
ELSE
    XChange <-- 1
ENDIF

IF DeltaY < 0
    YChange <-- -1
    DeltaY = -DeltaY
ELSE
    YChange <-- 1
ENDIF

ERROR <-- 0
i <-- 0

IF DeltaX < DeltaY
    Length <-- DeltaY + 1
    LOOP WHILE i < Length
        <we have our current X/Y here...>
        Y <-- Y + YChange
        Error <-- Error + DeltaX
        IF Error > DeltaY
            X <-- X + XChange
            Error <-- Error - DeltaY
        ENDIF
        i <-- i + 1
    ENDLOOP
ELSE
    Length <-- DeltaX + 1
    LOOP WHILE i < Length
        <we have our current X/Y here...>
        X <-- X + XChange
        Error <-- Error + DeltaY
        IF Error > DeltaX
            Y <-- Y + YChange
            Error <-- Error - DeltaX
        ENDIF
        i <-- i + 1
    ENDLOOP
ENDIF

;--------------------

> I have only so far managed to move the sprite between points using
> acceleration/deceleration methods - which sounds impressive but really
> doesn't suit what I want! :(

I'm sure the above code can be redesigned to work in various
jumps rather than pixel perfect lines.

> BTW, I've just unsubscribed due to the unbelievable amount of Blitz
> messages clogging up my mailbox - so PLEASE mail me direct.
> Is it possible for me to send messages to the list if unsubscribed? 

Ahh, thats a shame. Now only blitz-list members will see the
answer which I think is VERY important piece of information!
Really, this is a "give and take" list which means you should
be available to help others when possible If you're not a member
then it becomes "take" only. Ahh well, the mailing list is available
for read-only on aminet each month, LOL :)

Cheers,

-- 
< Paul Burkey - http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk >



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_562" "Re: Straight lines"
 (Eudora Internet Mail Server 2.2); Wed, 25 Nov 1998 12:50:26 +0100
Date: Wed, 25 Nov 1998 13:30:54 +0100
From: Manfred Linzner <manfred.linzner@munich.netsurf.de>
X-Accept-Language: en
 	Hrafn <jhines1@mail.usyd.edu.au>
Subject: Re: Straight lines
Encoding: 7bit


> 
> Hey all,
> 
> I need help! :(
> 
> Does anyone know the basic principle (code) for a sprite to move in a
> *direct* straight line from one point to another at a *constant* speed?
> (I say `basic principle' because Blitz isn't the language I'm currently
> using for my programming).
> 
> I have only so far managed to move the sprite between points using
> acceleration/deceleration methods - which sounds impressive but really
> doesn't suit what I want! :(


;***************Start*****************

xstart.q=50
ystart.q=70
xend.q=190
yend.q=10

speed.q=100  ; how many iterations between start and enn

xdif.q=(xstart-xend)/speed
ydif.q=(ystart-yend)/speed

for a=0 to speed-1
	displaysprite 0,0,xtart,ystart,0
	xstart+xdif:ystart+ydif
	vwait
next a

;****************END*****************

Hope this works for you..  wrote it down without testing

-- 
