On 25-Nov-98, Paul Burkey wrote:
> Hi,

> I'd recomend Bresenham's Line Algorithm which is shown here
> in the folowing non language specific code....

> ;---------------------------------
> 
> (Given A(x1,y1) and B(x2,y2) and that the line is from A to B)
> 
> X <-- x1
> Y <-- y1

Sorry if this is a dumb question, but could you please explain what the
"<--" operator means?  I've never seen this one before.  I was guessing it
was the same as "=", but then "=" appears in other places.  Thanks.
> 
> DeltaX <-- x2 - x1
> DeltaY <-- y2 - y1
> 
> IF DeltaX < 0
>    XChange <-- -1
>    DeltaX = -DeltaX
> ELSE
>    XChange <-- 1
> ENDIF
> 
> IF DeltaY < 0
>    YChange <-- -1
>    DeltaY = -DeltaY
> ELSE
>    YChange <-- 1
> ENDIF
> 
> ERROR <-- 0
> i <-- 0
> 
> IF DeltaX < DeltaY
>    Length <-- DeltaY + 1
>    LOOP WHILE i < Length
>        <we have our current X/Y here...>
>        Y <-- Y + YChange
>        Error <-- Error + DeltaX
>        IF Error > DeltaY
>            X <-- X + XChange
>            Error <-- Error - DeltaY
>        ENDIF
>        i <-- i + 1
>    ENDLOOP
> ELSE
>    Length <-- DeltaX + 1
>    LOOP WHILE i < Length
>        <we have our current X/Y here...>
>        X <-- X + XChange
>        Error <-- Error + DeltaY
>        IF Error > DeltaX
>            Y <-- Y + YChange
>            Error <-- Error - DeltaX
>        ENDIF
>        i <-- i + 1
>    ENDLOOP
> ENDIF
> 

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_568" "Re: Straight lines"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Thu, 26 Nov 1998 02:46:34 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
Date: Thu, 26 Nov 1998 02:40:38 +0000
Subject: Re: Straight lines

Hi,

>> (Given A(x1,y1) and B(x2,y2) and that the line is from A to B)
>> 
>> X <-- x1
>> Y <-- y1

> Sorry if this is a dumb question, but could you please explain what the
> "<--" operator means?  I've never seen this one before.  I was guessing it
> was the same as "=", but then "=" appears in other places.  Thanks.

sorry, it's just pseudo-code which is simple to port to any language. You'll
find many types of pseudo-code, some standard and some 'made up on
the spot' and they all use their own rules. I don't know if this flavour of
pseudo-code is a standard one, i din't actually construct it myself.

>> X <-- x1

It does indeed mean '='... I'm not sure why <-- was used.
 
>>    DeltaX = -DeltaX

I suppose the '=' is used in a slightly different context here but you're
right to say that '=' would have been enough.

Cheers,

-- 
< Paul Burkey - http://www.sneech.demon.co.uk >

