@NODE "Mail_576" "Re: Text and windows"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Fri, 20 Nov 1998 18:09:24 -0500
Subject: Re: Text and windows

Hi M.

On 20-Nov-98, M. Misic wrote:
> Am 20-Nov-98 schrieb Rui Carvalho:
> 
>>> Hello Blitzers,
>> 
>>> what exactly i have to do, that every printed text in a window reaches
> the
>>> right end, it should continue in a new line ?
>> 
>> Use Nprint, which inserts a LF and CR at the end of the phrase.
>> Or CHR$(10) at the end of the phrase..
> 
> Uhh....sorry but it seems, that my english is so sad, that you don't
> understand what i mean.

Don't feel bad, my English is sad too, and I have been speaking it all my
life  ;)
> 
> My problem was like this:
> 
> If i put a text into a window by #NPrint#, sometimes this text is longer
> than
> the window is width.
> Now, wenn the printed text will reach the end of the window, i want to
> continue in a new line...

You can do it like this:

* Find the available width of your window (you can use Innerwidth command
for this)

* Use the system TextFit_ command on your text line.  It tells you how many
characters would fit in the given space using the window's font.

* If the whole string won't fit, you break it into 2 strings by searching
backward for a space character.  Now split the string, and Nprint the first
one.

* Send the 2nd string back to the TextFit_ command, and try again.


There is a source using the TextFit_ command on my web page.  It is part of
the text reader in a window example.  Maybe this would help you.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




