@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_593" "Re: To use Deflibs or not to use Deflibs..."
          (Post.Office MTA Undefined release Undefined
          ID# 0-52107U250000L250000S0V35) with SMTP id net
          for <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>; Sun, 22 Nov 1998 00:38:04 +0000
From: "Xyz Scott" <xyz.scott@virgin.net>
Subject: Re: To use Deflibs or not to use Deflibs...
Date: Sun, 22 Nov 1998 00:32:53 -0000
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

On 21st-Nov-1998, James L. Boyd churned out *this* drivel:

>Hi all,

>Somebody mentioned getting rid of deflibs as it's not needed and
>Blitz would use the installed libs automatically...

>I've just tried renaming deflibs and running Blitz, and it doesn't
>use any of the libs in my Blitzlibs: setup...

>What's the deal here?

OK.  I thought I'd try and figure this deflibs thing out once and for all.
I have just stuck with my trusty deflibs file up until now, but it would
appear that you can dispense with it by doing the following....
Create a drawer in your 'Blitz' drawer called 'UserLibs'.  Then, in
your 'BlitzLibs' drawer, there should be two drawers called 'AmigaLibs'
and 'OtherLibs'.  Copy both of these straight into the newly created
'UserLibs' drawer, delete or rename your deflibs file, depending on
how brave you are, and then crank up Blitz.  If all goes well, all your
libs should load automatically.

Regards

Scott

xyz.scott@virgin.net




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_594" "Re: To use Deflibs or not to use Deflibs..."
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sun, 22 Nov 1998 18:16:12 -0500
Subject: Re: To use Deflibs or not to use Deflibs...

Hi Xyz

On 21-Nov-98, Xyz Scott wrote:
> On 21st-Nov-1998, James L. Boyd churned out *this* drivel:
> 
>> Hi all,
> 
>> Somebody mentioned getting rid of deflibs as it's not needed and
>> Blitz would use the installed libs automatically...
> 
>> I've just tried renaming deflibs and running Blitz, and it doesn't
>> use any of the libs in my Blitzlibs: setup...
> 
>> What's the deal here?
> 
> OK.  I thought I'd try and figure this deflibs thing out once and for
all.
> I have just stuck with my trusty deflibs file up until now, but it would
> appear that you can dispense with it by doing the following....
> Create a drawer in your 'Blitz' drawer called 'UserLibs'.  Then, in
> your 'BlitzLibs' drawer, there should be two drawers called 'AmigaLibs'
> and 'OtherLibs'.  Copy both of these straight into the newly created
> 'UserLibs' drawer, delete or rename your deflibs file, depending on
> how brave you are, and then crank up Blitz.  If all goes well, all your
> libs should load automatically.

Which brings up the next question:  If you are not using a DefLibs (and one
of the library tools to make it) how do you know if there are any number
clashes in any new libraries that you are adding?

(Short of loading 'em all up in a hex editor and checking the numbers, I
mean)

I suppose what I really mean, is there any reason to NOT have a DefLibs? 
Yeah, it takes up a bit of disk space.  But Blitz seems to load up faster
with a DefLibs, and really it's no extra trouble to make it once I've
already run DefLibMan to check for clashing library numbers.

Just my two cents  ;)

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_595" "Re: To use Deflibs or not to use Deflibs..."
          (Post.Office MTA Undefined release Undefined
          ID# 0-52107U250000L250000S0V35) with SMTP id net
          for <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>; Mon, 23 Nov 1998 08:29:29 +0000
From: "Xyz Scott" <xyz.scott@virgin.net>
Subject: Re: To use Deflibs or not to use Deflibs...
Date: Mon, 23 Nov 1998 08:24:06 -0000
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit

On 23rd-Nov-1998 Curt Esser electronically said:

>Which brings up the next question:  If you are not using a DefLibs (and one
>of the library tools to make it) how do you know if there are any number
>clashes in any new libraries that you are adding?


You don't.  Not until you go to use a command from one of the clashing
libs.  Then what happens is you type a command, and it spookily tokenizes
into another command.  The library that Blitz loaded first gets priority.

>I suppose what I really mean, is there any reason to NOT have a DefLibs?
>Yeah, it takes up a bit of disk space.  But Blitz seems to load up faster
>with a DefLibs, and really it's no extra trouble to make it once I've
>already run DefLibMan to check for clashing library numbers.


I agree.  Even after finding out how you can dispense with deflibs, I still
use
it for those very reasons.  I'm sure we can spare a couple of hundred Kb on
our hard drives, and floppy users really do need deflibs otherwise Blitz
takes
about 3 weeks to load.

>Just my two cents  ;)

Mine too   (;

Regards

Scott

xyz.scott@virgin.net




@ENDNODE
