@NODE "Mail_600" "Trivial pointers question..."
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Sat, 7 Nov 1998 00:57:14 +0000
From: James L Boyd <jamesboyd@velvety.demon.co.uk>
Date: Sat, 07 Nov 1998 00:53:21 +0000
Subject: Trivial pointers question...

Hi everyone,

I've just got a not-too-important question about pointers :

I know that pointers are supposed to start with "*"

    eg *lock.l=Lock_(blahblah)

But I also know that they often work without the "*"

So basically,is the "*" a necessity,or is it just for convention &
recognition?

See ya,

-- 
James L Boyd - Team *AMIGA*
jamesboyd@velvety.demon.co.uk
------------------------------------------------------------------
"I want to hear the holy rampage/I don't mind a little ear damage" 
- Frank Black,"I Want Rock 'n' Roll" ( www.goodnoise.com )



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_601" "Re: Trivial pointers question..."
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Sat, 7 Nov 1998 12:52:36 +0000
From: Paul Burkey <burkey@bigfoot.com>
Date: Sat, 07 Nov 1998 12:04:48 +0000
Subject: Re: Trivial pointers question...

Hi,

> I've just got a not-too-important question about pointers :
> I know that pointers are supposed to start with "*"

>    eg *lock.l=Lock_(blahblah)

> But I also know that they often work without the "*"

> So basically,is the "*" a necessity,or is it just for convention &
> recognition?

Whenyou are actually 'using' pointers you must include the '*' 
because without the '*' you'll be refering to a different varialbe
altogether. So '*lock' is a pointer to a 'long' and 'lock' is a new
variable which hasn't yet been used...

Somtimes you would see somthing like:

lock.l=Lock_(blaablaa

In this case it is not a pointer but a regular variable. I guess the
Lock_() function returns an address... addresses can be 'stored'
in a 'long' variable but they can also be assigned to a pointer.
You're getting mixed up with two different things. Both are valid
ways to accept a returned address, and both have their own uses.

I suppose it depends if you wanted to deal with the address itself
(using a variable) or the data the address points to (pointer).

Cheers,

-- 
< Paul Burkey - burkey.home.ml.org >

"I went to the museum where they have all the heads and arms
from all the statues that are in all the other museums..."
-- Stephen Wright




