@NODE "Mail_606" "Re: Variables in Asm functions"
 (envelope-from D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk)
    2 Nov 98 10:10:43 0
From: "David Mcminn" <D.McMinn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Mon, 2 Nov 1998 10:10:30 -0000
encoding: Quoted-printable
Subject: Re: Variables in Asm functions

On 29 Oct 98, at 21:19, Mathias PARNAUDEAU wrote:

> I want to make an ASM function and I need to declare functions inside.
> What is the way ? Declare them at the end of the function (and before
> AsmExit) as dc.b, other ?
> 
> Any ideas ? They're welcome.

 Do it on the stack, and then use an address register (such as a4) 
like Blitz does. I can't test this just now as the Debugger crashes 
WinUAE. However, what you want to do is start off with a LINK to 
allocate some stack space and get the pointer to your variable base. 
Then use the variables by using offsets along with the variable base 
pointer. Finally to clean up, just do an UNLK and then an RTS.

 Mind you, this will probably get screwed up if you need to pass 
parameters to your function, using Blitz syntax (i.e. ASM1{a,b}) as 
these variables will be created using the above method by Blitz, and 
everything may die. Is it possible to pass parameters by loading the 
registers then calling the function with no parameters without them 
getting destroyed? Or you could always use this as a subroutine, as 
variable space is local to the subroutine.

Anyway, an example (which I can't test). If this doesn't work, try 
doing it as a subroutine. This is a simple example, which you would 
normally use registers for.

; 8<-----8<-----8<-----8<-----8<-----8<-----8<-----8<-----

#VARIABLESIZE =3D -8; We have 8 bytes to store variables in.

; Note that no offsets are 0 as this is where the original a4 is
; kept, which is slightly different from Blitz, it uses 0 offsets.
#VAR1_L =3D -4; Offset for var1.l
#VAR2_L - -8; Offset for var2.l

Function.l ASM1{}
	; Get variable base pointer and allocate stack space
	LINK a4,#VARIABLESIZE

	; var1.l =3D 4
	MOVE.l #4,#VAR1_L(a4)

	; var2.l =3D var1 * 3, I know that I've multiplied a
	; long by a word, but I wasn't sure if MULS.l exists
	MOVE.l #VAR1_L(a4),d0
	MULS.w #3,d0
	MOVE.l d0,#VAR2_L(a4)

	; Hopefully, Function Return var2.l
	MOVE.l #VAR2_L(a4),d0

	; Clean up and exit
	UNLK a4
	RTS
end funtion

; Should print 12
Nprint ASM1
Clickmouse
end

|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
  d.mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk ICQ=3D16827694


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_607" "Vertical ScanRates"
 for blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie; Tue, 1 Dec 1998 17:34:24 +0000
From: Daniel Allsopp <daniel@thesnakepit.demon.co.uk>
Date: Tue, 01 Dec 1998 16:56:14 +0000
Subject: Vertical ScanRates

Hi all,

I'm trying to figure out the FramesPerSecond my game currently runs at.
However, I'm unsure whether I check to see if the Timer is >49 (=50) or
greater than the vertical scanrate of te display.

Obviously PAL modes all have a VSR of 50, and that's what I started using,
however, my cybergraphics screen modes have vertical rates of 67 and 70
etc.

Now would I always check to see if the timer is >50 or >VSR of the
screenmode?

Also, is there a way of finding the VSR of the screenmode? I know all AGA
modes have fixed rates but you can change all of this when you define a new
CyberGraphX mode, which is why everyone has different ModeID's for the same
screenmode.

Thanks for any help 

-- 
Cheers,
    Daniel

