@NODE "Mail_608" "Waiting For Sound Samples"
From: Jake Frederick <gonzo@acadia.net>
Date: Mon, 23 Nov 1998 19:47:49 +0500
Subject: Waiting For Sound Samples

   The game I am writing requires speech between two characters. I need to
play a sample and wait until that sample is finished playing to play another
one while keeping the flow of the rest of the game uninterupted. Is there any
way to tell if a sound channel is free before playing a sample? If not is
there another method equally suitable?
-- 
-If the doors of perception were cleansed everything would appear to man as it
truly is, infinite.-



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_609" "Re: Waiting For Sound Samples"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Tue, 24 Nov 1998 05:06:53 -0500
Subject: Re: Waiting For Sound Samples

Warning: This is a message in MIME format. Your mail reader does not
support MIME. Some parts of this message will be readable as plain text.
To see the rest, you will need to upgrade your mail reader.


--BOUNDARY.1748883592.1

Hi Jake

On 23-Nov-98, Jake Frederick wrote:
>   The game I am writing requires speech between two characters. I need to
> play a sample and wait until that sample is finished playing to play
> another one while keeping the flow of the rest of the game uninterupted.
Is
> there any way to tell if a sound channel is free before playing a sample?
> If not is there another method equally suitable?

I struggled for ages trying to get Blitz's sound channel interrupts working,
but had no luck  (lot's of spectacular crashes, though!)

Anyway, here is what I came up with.  It works pretty well - not
split-second accurate, but close enough.

Of course, you don't want to use the Vwait as in the example.  Instead, I
set up an array of the playing time of each sample as I load them.

I also set up a Vblank interrupt (this one does work!) which simply counts
down a variable to zero.

When I play a sample, I set this counter variable to the sample's playing
time.  Now, you can check this variable each loop of your main code.  If it
is zero, the sound is finished, and you can take the appropriate action -
play the next sample, stop the guy's mouth moving, or whatever.

If you need to, you could even set up 4 counters, one for each sound
channel.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/


--BOUNDARY.1748883592.1
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="soundlen.asc"
Encoding: quoted-printable

;By Curt Esser
;camge@ix.netcom.com
;use in any way you like
;
; Determines the playing time (in Vblanks) of an iff sample
;
WBenchToFront_
WbToScreen 0
If NTSC=3DTrue
  vrate=3D60                                        ;adjust for NTSC or P=
AL
Else
  vrate=3D50
EndIf
NPrint "Vblank:",vrate
MaxLen pa$=3D200
MaxLen fi$=3D200
Repeat
  snd$=3DASLFileRequest$ ("load a sound",pa$,fi$)
  If snd$=3D"" Then End
  Free Sound 0
  LoadSound 0,snd$
  period=3DPeek.w(Addr Sound (0)+4)                 ;get the period from =
sound object
  lngth.l=3D(Peek.w(Addr Sound (0)+6) AND $FFFF)*2  ;get the length from =
sound object
  frequency.f =3D 3579440/period                    ;convert to true freq=
uency
  delay.w=3Dlngth/(frequency/vrate)                 ;convert to playing t=
ime in VBlanks
  delay+5                                         ;add a bit of padding f=
or short samples
  NPrint" "
  NPrint "Sample: ",fi$
  NPrint "Period: ",period
  NPrint "Length: ",lngth
  NPrint "Delay : ",delay
  Sound 0,15
  VWait delay
  Sound 0,15
Forever
End



--BOUNDARY.1748883592.1--




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_610" "Re: Waiting For Sound Samples"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sun, 29 Nov 1998 19:09:24 -0500
Subject: Re: Waiting For Sound Samples

Hi Jake

On 28-Nov-98, Jake Frederick wrote:

>   The code you gave me worked fine when I just used a delay that stopped
> the program flow, but for some reason when I tried to set up a counter it
> changed the length of the delay to the value of the vrate variable. So in
> my case all of the samples simply wait for a count of 60 before the sound
> channel is free. This is the basic code I'm using:

I tried the code you posted, and it seemed to work fine with any samples I
tested on it, both long and short.

Maybe you have a "mangled" sound sample?  I have found a few of these, that
will play OK on some software but not with others.  Try loading it in a
sound editor and re-saving it to see what happens.

Or maybe there is something else in your code somewhere else that is
interfering?


                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/




