@NODE "Mail_623" "Would YOU like a new Blitz Compiler?"
From: "Matthew Parsons" <billyray@enterprise.net>
Organization: Private User
Date: 29 Nov 98 23:15:54 +0000
Subject: Would YOU like a new Blitz Compiler?
Encoding: 7bit

It seems that only Frederic can  be bothered to make a new compiler,
but (And I don't blame him) he wants to use his own command set. Also
he seems to have based it around 68000 ASM!!!!!

So now I'm a little irritated, so much so that I've started coding my
own Compiler.

My main goal was to make a CPU independant compiler, this is so that
the system is as future proof as possible.

Well Here it is:




                         Blitz Basic 2 Upgrade

This is a small document covering my new Blitz basic compiler format.
I have decided to make my own Blitz Basic compatable compiler, this is my
first compiler for a programming language which I did not design. 

With this I want to try to tell you how my compiler works, and hopefully 
you will be able to help me improve and add to it.

I will firstly list my goals:

1. Make a Blitz Basic 2 Source Code compatable compiler.
2. Make it CPU independant.
3. Make it future proof.
4. Allow easy Third Party Expasion.


The first goal is obvious, and needs no explaination.
 
Ok, I had better explain how goal 2 is realised. I have decided on the 
bilayer compiler system. This is where the Blitz commands are compiled to
an intermediate code, then the intermediate code is compiled to the target
CPU's asm.

A similar system would be to:

Covert Blitz Source to C source, then compile the C source to a target CPU. 
This can then be assembled. 

BLITZ---->C
       C---->ASM
  ASM---->Machine Code

But I have a long established hatred of C so I will use my own intermediate
code. I have dicided to call my intermediate code PsudoASM (not a spelling 
mistake). So we now have this situation:

        BLITZ---->PsudoASM
PsudoASM---->ASM (68K or PPC)
          ASM---->Machine Code


I will try to make PsudoASM as close to PPC Asm as possible, this is will
result in the 68K version being less efficient than it could be, but this
will still be better than the original compiler. I have decided to do it 
this way because the PPC is a fairly typical RISC machine and all future
CPU's will be RISC.

Now for the technical bit :).
The Variables, pointers and basic Blitz syntax will be handled by the 
compiler, that is to say that these parts of the language will be hard coded
into the compiler. (And also The simple control structures)

The commands and instructions are stored as a separate file. This file is 
called PrimaryMagma.lib.

All commands in the PrimaryMagma.lib are stored in this format:

</ADD/>                      ; Command Name
</n1,n2/>                    ; Command Parameters
</Add n1,n2/>                ; PsudoASM code for the command
</FFF/>                      ; F ree  F or  F uture
<//>                             ; Return parameters (in this case,none) 
</Add Variable,Variable/>    ; Description of command
 *                               ; End of Command, marker

The PrimaryMagma.lib file is a simple ascii text containing all the blitz
commands in the format above. Commands can be added simply by adding 
more commands in the above format to the file.


The Second external file is PsudoASM.lib. This file contains the PsudoASM
instructions.

All instructions are stored in this format:

</ADD/>        ; PsudoASM instruction
</n1,n2/>      ; PsudoASM instruction parameters
</Add n1,n2/>  ; 68K or PPC version of instruction (in this case, 68k)
</FFF/>        ; F ree F or F uture
*              ; End of instruction marker

The PsudoASM.lib can be made in any version, that is to say that any CPU's
instructions can be used as the final code. This will allow future CPU's
to be taken into account, with out the need of rewriting the 
PrimaryMAGMA.lib.

The compiler outputs ASM source file that is ready to be assembled using 
a standard public domain assembler.

If you can improved or help in the implementation of this design then 
please contact me at:

billyray@enterprise.net

if you want to use this system in your own compiler then please go ahead,
but try to keep your system as compatible to this one as possible and also
credit me in your documentation.

Thanx

On a final note, I think Blitz Mode should be removed. Well, maybe we should
keep it until we have a PPC version of the OS. A Blitz mode game would run
on a PPC quite happily, but an amiga mode version would be doing lots of
context switches, this means a slow down.


@ENDNODE
